30-129 BC|Great King (Shah) of Persia]]|years=330\u2013323&nbsp;BC}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of pharaohs#Argead Dynasty|Pharaoh of Egypt]]|years=332\u2013323&nbsp;BC}}\n{{S-new|creation}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Lord of Asia]]|years=331\u2013323&nbsp;BC}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Kings of Macedon}}\n{{Hellenistic rulers}}\n{{Pharaohs |late}}\n{{Shahnameh}}\n{{Ancient Greece topics}}\n{{Plutarch}}\n{{Ancient Greek and Roman wars |collapsed}}\n{{Empires}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alexander the Great}}\n[[Category:Alexander the Great| ]]\n[[Category:356 BC births]]\n[[Category:323 BC deaths]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC Macedonian monarchs]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC Pharaohs]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC Babylonian kings]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC Macedonians]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC rulers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Macedonian generals]]\n[[Category:Ancient Pellaeans]]\n[[Category:Argead kings of Macedonia]]\n[[Category:City founders]]\n[[Category:Deified people]]\n[[Category:Hellenistic-era people]]\n[[Category:Monarchs of Persia]]\n[[Category:People in the Deuterocanonical books]]\n[[Category:Pharaohs of the Argead dynasty]]\n[[Category:Shahnameh characters]]\n[[Category:LGBT heads of state]]\n", "name_user": "Tony Keen2", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added ancient reference for quotation from Plutarch in Livius.org", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_the_Great"}
{"title_page": "Lautaro Baeza", "text_new": "{{short description|Argentine naturalized Chilean footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Lautaro Baeza\n| image       = [[File:LAUTARO BAEZA.jpg|150px]]\n| fullname    = Lautaro Manuel Baeza\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1990|2|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Merlo, Buenos Aires|Merlo]], [[Argentina]]\n| height      = {{height|m=1.72}}\n| position    = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| years1      = 2010\u20132012 | clubs1 = [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield|V\u00e9lez Sarsfield]]               | caps1 = 0  | goals1 = 0\n| years2      = 2011\u20132012 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[CA Platense|Platense]] (loan) | caps2 = 0  | goals2 = 0\n| years3      = 2012\u20132013 | clubs3 = [[Sportivo Las Parejas]]          | caps3 = 14 | goals3 = 0\n| years4      = 2013\u20132014 | clubs4 = [[C.S.D. Rangers|Rangers]]        | caps4 = 15 | goals4 = 0\n| years5      = 2015      | clubs5 = [[Deportivo Merlo]]               | caps5 = 31 | goals5 = 4\n| years6      = 2016      | clubs6 = [[Sportivo Patria]]               | caps6 = 11 | goals6 = 1\n| years7      = 2016\u20132019 | clubs7 = [[Sportivo Barracas]]             | caps7 = 69 | goals7 = 4\n| pcupdate    = 30 March 2020\n}}\n'''Lautaro Manuel Baeza''' (born 17 February 1990) is an [[Argentine people|Argentine]]\u2013born [[Chilean people|Chilean]] [[association football|footballer]]. His last club was [[Sportivo Barracas]].\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.bdfa.com.ar/jugadores-LAUTARO-MANUEL-BAEZA-87896.html Profile at BDFA] {{in lang|es}}\n* {{Soccerway|lautaro-manuel-baeza/249005}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baeza, Lautaro}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Chilean footballers]]\n[[Category:Chilean expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield footballers]]\n[[Category:Rangers de Talca footballers]]\n[[Category:Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Chile]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n{{Argentina-footy-defender-stub}}\n{{Chile-footy-defender-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Argentine naturalized Chilean footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Lautaro Baeza\n| image       = [[File:LAUTARO BAEZA.jpg|150px]]\n| fullname    = Lautaro Manuel Baeza\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1990|2|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Merlo, Buenos Aires|Merlo]], [[Argentina]]\n| height      = {{height|m=1.72}}\n| position    = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| years1      = 2010\u20132012 | clubs1 = [[V\u00e9lez Sarsfield]]               | caps1 = 0  | goals1 = 0\n| years2      = 2011\u20132012 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[CA Platense|Platense]] (loan) | caps2 = 0  | goals2 = 0\n| years3      = 2012\u20132013 | clubs3 = [[Sportivo Las Parejas]]          | caps3 = 14 | goals3 = 0\n| years4      = 2013\u20132014 | clubs4 = [[C.S.D. Rangers|Rangers]]        | caps4 = 15 | goals4 = 0\n| years5      = 2015      | clubs5 = [[Deportivo Merlo]]               | caps5 = 31 | goals5 = 4\n| years6      = 2016      | clubs6 = [[Sportivo Patria]]               | caps6 = 11 | goals6 = 1\n| years7      = 2016\u20132019 | clubs7 = [[Sportivo Barracas]]             | caps7 = 69 | goals7 = 4\n| pcupdate    = 30 March 2020\n}}\n'''Lautaro Manuel Baeza''' (born 17 February 1990) is an [[Argentine people|Argentine]]\u2013born [[Chilean people|Chilean]] [[association football|footballer]]. His last club was [[Sportivo Barracas]].\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.bdfa.com.ar/jugadores-LAUTARO-MANUEL-BAEZA-87896.html Profile at BDFA] {{in lang|es}}\n* {{Soccerway|lautaro-manuel-baeza/249005}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baeza, Lautaro}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Argentine footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Chilean footballers]]\n[[Category:Chilean expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield footballers]]\n[[Category:Rangers de Talca footballers]]\n[[Category:Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Chile]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Argentina]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n{{Argentina-footy-defender-stub}}\n{{Chile-footy-defender-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toV\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield(link changed toClub Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez Sarsfield) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lautaro_Baeza"}
{"title_page": "Burning Fight", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Burning Fight\n|image         = Burning Fight arcade flyer.jpg\n|caption       = European Arcade flyer with art by [[Shinkiro]]\n|developer     = [[SNK]]\n|publisher     = SNK<br />[[D4 Enterprise]]<br /><small>(Virtual Console)</small><br />[[Hamster Corporation|HAMSTER Corporation]] <small>(PS4/Switch/Xbox One)</small>\n|producer      = [[Eikichi Kawasaki]]\n|designer      = Naoto Abe<ref name=\"WFT1545\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|title=|magazine=[[Famitsu]]|issue=1545|publisher=Gzbrain|date=July 26, 2018|page=|lang=ja}} ([http://www.onemillionpower.com/snk-40th-anniversary-talking-to-the-snk-creators-that-made-history/ Translation] by One Million Power. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223213831/http://www.onemillionpower.com/snk-40th-anniversary-talking-to-the-snk-creators-that-made-history/|date=2019-12-23}}).</ref>\n|composer      = Yasumasa Yamada\n|platforms     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo AES]], [[Neo Geo CD]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Virtual Console]], [[Xbox One]]}}\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[1991 in video gaming|1991]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|WW|20 May 1991}} '''Neo Geo AES'''{{vgrelease|JP|9 August 1991|NA|9 August 1991|EU|9 August 1991}} '''Neo Geo CD'''{{vgrelease|JP|9 September [[1994 in video games|1994]]|NA|October [[1996 in video games|1996]]}} '''Virtual Console'''{{vgrelease|NA|14 April [[2008 in video games|2008]]|JP|7 May 2008|EU|30 May 2008|AU|30 May 2008}} '''Nintendo Switch'''{{vgrelease|WW|28 September [[2017 in video games|2017]]}} '''Xbox One'''{{vgrelease|WW|28 September 2017}} '''PlayStation 4'''{{vgrelease|JP|28 September 2017|WW|11 October 2017}}}}\n|genre         = [[Beat 'em up]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Cooperative gameplay|Co-op]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo MVS]]\n|cpu           = [[Motorola 68000|M68000]] (@ 12 [[Hertz|MHz]]),<br />[[Zilog Z80|Z80A]] (@ 4 MHz)\n|sound         = [[Yamaha YM2610|YM2610]] (@ 8 MHz)<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=869&page=2#18346|title=SNK NeoGeo MVS Hardware (SNK)|website=system16.com|accessdate=2019-06-02}}</ref>\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 304 \u00d7 224 pixels (Horizontal), 4096 [[color]]s\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Burning Fight'''''|\u30d0\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u30fb\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8|''B\u0101ningu Faito''||lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[beat 'em up]] [[arcade game]] released by [[SNK]] in 1991 for the [[Neo Geo (console)|Neo Geo]] [[MVS]] system. Introduced to capture a share in the then-popular beat 'em ups market, it was meant to compete with [[Techn\u014ds Japan|Techn\u014ds]]' ''[[Double Dragon]]'', the leader of the genre at the time. Three years after its release in the arcades and on the [[Neo Geo (console)|Neo Geo AES]], it was released on [[Neo Geo CD]] as the only other home version.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePro_The_Cutting_Edge_Spring_1996#page/n109/mode/2up|title=Neo\u2022Geo CD: The Arcade In A Box - Burning Fight|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=Premiere Supplement|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=Spring 1996|page=104}}</ref>\n\nThe game is produced by Eikichi Kawasaki, one of SNK's founders and the man behind various well-known SNK titles, such as ''[[Fatal Fury]]'' and ''[[Samurai Shodown]]'' series.\n\nA re-released version of ''Burning Fight'' is included in ''[[SNK Arcade Classics Vol. 1]]'', which was released for the [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation Portable]] and [[Wii]] in 2008.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:NEOGEO Burning Fight.png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot showcasing the first boss.]]\n''Burning Fight'' follows a formula and concepts commonly seen in titles of this genre, such as [[Streets of Rage]], ''Double Dragon'' and ''[[Final Fight]]'': balanced character selection, objects and weapons found on the ground cause greater damage to opponents, and semi-interactive environments (players can damage objects like phone booths and [[street sign]]s along the way). The game is set in a fictional version of [[Osaka]] city (during a train station scene the platform even shows an \"[[Umeda Station|Umida]]\" station sign).\n\nThere are three playable characters, each with their own levels of strength, agility and special moves: Ryu is quick but weak, Billy is slow but very strong, and Duke is a more balanced hitter. One element that helps the game stand out from its competition is mini-stages, where the player must defeat some enemies in a short period of time in order to win prizes.\n\nAntagonists are members of Heiwa-Gumi, a Japanese [[yakuza]] gang, though there are a few Caucasian bosses and mid-level bosses (including three wrestling characters, Tom Anderson, Gary Powell and the Mad Dilly, modelled after [[Hulk Hogan]] and [[Randy Savage]]), and the final boss is [[Italians|Italian]] mob boss '''Castella''' (''Casterora'' in [[Japanese language|Japanese]]). Moreover, the game has no individual endings, no matter which character has been chosen. After defeating Castella, players are presented with various scenes of the game along with the credits, and finally a group picture of the main characters.\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n|title     = Contemporary reception\n|GR        = (Neo Geo) 55%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamerankings.com/neo/582031-burning-fight/index.html|title=Burning Fight for NeoGeo|work=[[GameRankings]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=2019|accessdate=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|Allgame   = (Neo Geo) {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"AGNGbf\">{{cite web|last=Knight|first=Kyle|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16994&tab=review|title=Burning Fight (Neo Geo Advanced Entertainment System) - Review|work=[[AllGame]]|publisher=[[All Media Network]]|date=1998|access-date=2019-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115224240/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16994&tab=review|archive-date=2014-11-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|CVG       = (Neo Geo) 92 / 100<ref name=\"CVGNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last1=Rand|first1=Paul|last2=Boone|first2=Tim|url=https://archive.org/stream/computer-video-games-magazine-122/CVG122_Jan_1992#page/n33/mode/2up|title=Reviews - Neo Geo -- Burning Fight|magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]]|issue=122|publisher=[[Future plc|Future Publishing]]|date=January 1992|pages=34\u201335}}</ref>\n|GamePro   = (Neo Geo) 24 / 25<ref name=\"GProNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last=Quan|first=Slasher|url=https://archive.org/details/GamePro_Issue_030_January_1992/page/n103|title=Neo Geo For Real! - Burning Fight|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=30|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=January 1992|pages=101\u2013102}}</ref>\n|rev1      = ''[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]''\n|rev1Score = (Neo Geo) 92%<ref name=\"C+NGbf\">{{cite magazine|author1=Loulou|author2=El Nio Nio|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=8895&album=oui|title=Neo Geo Review - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]|issue=5|publisher=[[:fr:M.E.R.7|M.E.R.7]]|date=January 1992|pages=34\u201335|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev2      = ''[[Hobby Consolas|Hobby Hi-Tech]]''\n|rev2Score = (Neo Geo CD) 4 / 10<ref name=\"HHiTechNGCDbf\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/HiTechMagazine/HiTech%2001#page/n28/mode/1up|title=Reportaje - Cl\u00e1sicos en CD -- Titulos disponibles para el nuevo formato de SNK: Burning Fight|magazine=[[Hobby Consolas|Hobby Hi-Tech]]|issue=1|publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]|date=March 1995|page=29|lang=es}}</ref>\n|rev3      = ''[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]''\n|rev3Score = (Neo Geo) 92%<ref name=\"JpadNGbf\">{{cite magazine|author1=Steph|last2=Demoly|first2=Jean-Marc|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=84&num=1771&album=oui|title=Test - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]|issue=2|publisher=[[:fr:Yellow Media|Yellow Media]]|date=November 1991|pages=122\u2013124|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev4      = ''[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]''\n|rev4Score = (Neo Geo) 92%<ref name=\"JNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last=Demoly|first=Jean-Marc|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Joystick/joystick_numero020/Joystick%20020%20-%20Page%20131%20(1991-10).jpg|title=Tests - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]|issue=20|publisher=[[:fr:Anuman Interactive|Anuman Interactive]]|date=October 1991|page=131|lang=fr|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|rev5      = ''[[:de:Mega Fun|Mega Fun]]''\n|rev5Score = (Neo Geo) 77%<ref name=\"MFNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last1=Noak|first1=Philipp|last2=Hellert|first2=Stefan|url=http://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=8807&s=3|title=Special - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:de:Mega Fun|Mega Fun]]|issue=11|publisher=[[:de:Computec Media Group|CT Computec Verlag GmbH & Co. KG]]|date=August 1993|pages=28\u201330|lang=de|access-date=2019-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021232116/http://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=8807&s=3|archive-date=2018-10-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev6      = ''[[:ja:\u30de\u30a4\u30b3\u30f3BASIC\u30de\u30ac\u30b8\u30f3|Micom BASIC Magazine]]''\n|rev6Score = (Neo Geo) {{Rating|3}}<ref name=\"MBASICMNGbf\">{{cite magazine|author1=Yanma|author2=Itabashi|url=https://archive.org/stream/micomBASIC_1992-07#page/n232/mode/1up|title=Super Soft \u5927\u7279\u96c6 - \u4eca\u3001\u300eNEO\u30fbGEO\u300f\u304c\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d\u3044\uff01: \u30d0\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8|magazine=[[:ja:\u30de\u30a4\u30b3\u30f3BASIC\u30de\u30ac\u30b8\u30f3|Micom BASIC Magazine]]|issue=121|publisher=[[:ja:\u96fb\u6ce2\u65b0\u805e\u793e|The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation]]|date=July 1992|page=209|lang=ja}}</ref>\n|rev7      = ''[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]''\n|rev7Score = (Neo Geo) 85%<ref name=\"PONGbf\">{{cite magazine|last=Drevet|first=Cyril|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=32&num=1063&album=oui|title=Tests De Jeux - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]|issue=16|publisher=[[:fr:M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition|M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition]]|date=January 1992|pages=80\u201381|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev8      = ''[[Sinclair User]]''\n|rev8Score = (Arcade) 74%<ref name=\"SUACbf\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/sinclair-user-magazine-113/SinclairUser_113_Jul_1991#page/n38/mode/1up|title=Coin Ops - Burning Fight \u2022 Neo Geo|magazine=[[Sinclair User]]|issue=113|publisher=[[Ascential|EMAP]]|date=July 1991|page=39}}</ref>\n}}\n\nWhile ''Burning Fight'' was successful critically,<ref name=\"VGNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last=Knauf|first=Andreas|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=5065&s=2|title=News - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=5|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=January 1992|pages=10\u201312|lang=de}}</ref> it received a lukewarm welcome by fans of the genre. The lack of popularity led the game to fail to have the impact SNK was hoping for and it was left behind its better known competitors. ''Sinclair User'' highlighted this sense of dullness by giving the game a rating of 74 and stating that, \"Burning Fight is a competent journey along the usual beat-'em-up road...\"<ref name=\"SUACbf\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Retrospective reviews ===\n{{Video game reviews\n|title = Retrospective assessments\n|GR    = (Switch) 30%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamerankings.com/switch/223218-aca-neogeo-burning-fight/index.html|title=ACA NeoGeo: Burning Fight for Nintendo Switch|work=[[GameRankings]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=2019|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|EuroG = (Wii) 7 / 10<ref name=\"EuroGVCbf\">{{cite web|last=Whitehead|first=Dan|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/virtual-console-roundup_8|title=Virtual Console Roundup - Paradroid, Burning Fight, Pokemon Puzzle League and Samurai Shodown|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network Ltd.|date=June 2, 2008|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|IGN   = (Wii) 4.5 / 10<ref name=\"IGNVCbf\">{{cite web|last=M. Thomas|first=Lucas|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2008/07/07/burning-fight-review|title=Burning Fight Review|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=July 7, 2008|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|NLife = (Wii) 5 / 10<ref name=\"NLifeVCbf\">{{cite web|last=McFerran|first=Damien|url=https://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/neogeo/burning_fight|title=Burning Fight Review (Neo Geo)|work=[[Nintendo Life]]|publisher=Nlife Media|date=May 31, 2008|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref><br />(Switch) 3 / 10<ref name=\"NLifeNSbf\">{{cite web|last=Frear|first=Dave|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/switch-eshop/burning_fight_neogeo|title=Burning Fight Review (Switch eShop / Neo Geo)|work=[[Nintendo Life]]|publisher=Nlife Media|date=October 2, 2017|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Burning Fight'' has been met with a much more mixed reception from critics since its release.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of Neo Geo games]]\n*[[NeoGeo Battle Coliseum]]\n*[[Double Dragon]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/arcade/575702-burning-fight ''Burning Fight''] at [[GameFAQs]]\n* [https://www.giantbomb.com/burning-fight/3030-16610/ ''Burning Fight''] at [[Giant Bomb]]\n* [https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=7242 ''Burning Fight''] at [[Killer List of Videogames]]\n* [https://www.mobygames.com/game/burning-fight ''Burning Fight''] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{Neo Geo}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Japan|Video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burning Fight}}\n[[Category:1991 video games]]\n[[Category:ACA Neo Geo games]]\n[[Category:Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:D4 Enterprise games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Neo Geo games]]\n[[Category:Neo Geo CD games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Network games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:SNK games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Burning Fight\n|image         = Burning Fight arcade flyer.jpg\n|caption       = European Arcade flyer with art by [[Shinkiro]]\n|developer     = [[SNK]]\n|publisher     = SNK<br />[[D4 Enterprise]]<br /><small>(Virtual Console)</small><br />[[Hamster Corporation|HAMSTER Corporation]] <small>(PS4/Switch/Xbox One)</small>\n|producer      = [[Eikichi Kawasaki]]\n|designer      = Naoto Abe<ref name=\"WFT1545\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|title=|magazine=[[Famitsu]]|issue=1545|publisher=Gzbrain|date=July 26, 2018|page=|lang=ja}}</ref>\n|composer      = Yasumasa Yamada\n|platforms     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo AES]], [[Neo Geo CD]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Virtual Console]], [[Xbox One]]}}\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[1991 in video gaming|1991]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|WW|20 May 1991}} '''Neo Geo AES'''{{vgrelease|JP|9 August 1991|NA|9 August 1991|EU|9 August 1991}} '''Neo Geo CD'''{{vgrelease|JP|9 September [[1994 in video games|1994]]|NA|October [[1996 in video games|1996]]}} '''Virtual Console'''{{vgrelease|NA|14 April [[2008 in video games|2008]]|JP|7 May 2008|EU|30 May 2008|AU|30 May 2008}} '''Nintendo Switch'''{{vgrelease|WW|28 September [[2017 in video games|2017]]}} '''Xbox One'''{{vgrelease|WW|28 September 2017}} '''PlayStation 4'''{{vgrelease|JP|28 September 2017|WW|11 October 2017}}}}\n|genre         = [[Beat 'em up]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Cooperative gameplay|Co-op]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo MVS]]\n|cpu           = [[Motorola 68000|M68000]] (@ 12 [[Hertz|MHz]]),<br />[[Zilog Z80|Z80A]] (@ 4 MHz)\n|sound         = [[Yamaha YM2610|YM2610]] (@ 8 MHz)<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=869&page=2#18346|title=SNK NeoGeo MVS Hardware (SNK)|website=system16.com|accessdate=2019-06-02}}</ref>\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 304 \u00d7 224 pixels (Horizontal), 4096 [[color]]s\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Burning Fight'''''|\u30d0\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u30fb\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8|''B\u0101ningu Faito''||lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[beat 'em up]] [[arcade game]] released by [[SNK]] in 1991 for the [[Neo Geo (console)|Neo Geo]] [[MVS]] system. Introduced to capture a share in the then-popular beat 'em ups market, it was meant to compete with [[Techn\u014ds Japan|Techn\u014ds]]' ''[[Double Dragon]]'', the leader of the genre at the time. Three years after its release in the arcades and on the [[Neo Geo (console)|Neo Geo AES]], it was released on [[Neo Geo CD]] as the only other home version.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePro_The_Cutting_Edge_Spring_1996#page/n109/mode/2up|title=Neo\u2022Geo CD: The Arcade In A Box - Burning Fight|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=Premiere Supplement|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=Spring 1996|page=104}}</ref>\n\nThe game is produced by Eikichi Kawasaki, one of SNK's founders and the man behind various well-known SNK titles, such as ''[[Fatal Fury]]'' and ''[[Samurai Shodown]]'' series.\n\nA re-released version of ''Burning Fight'' is included in ''[[SNK Arcade Classics Vol. 1]]'', which was released for the [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation Portable]] and [[Wii]] in 2008.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:NEOGEO Burning Fight.png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot showcasing the first boss.]]\n''Burning Fight'' follows a formula and concepts commonly seen in titles of this genre, such as [[Streets of Rage]], ''Double Dragon'' and ''[[Final Fight]]'': balanced character selection, objects and weapons found on the ground cause greater damage to opponents, and semi-interactive environments (players can damage objects like phone booths and [[street sign]]s along the way). The game is set in a fictional version of [[Osaka]] city (during a train station scene the platform even shows an \"[[Umeda Station|Umida]]\" station sign).\n\nThere are three playable characters, each with their own levels of strength, agility and special moves: Ryu is quick but weak, Billy is slow but very strong, and Duke is a more balanced hitter. One element that helps the game stand out from its competition is mini-stages, where the player must defeat some enemies in a short period of time in order to win prizes.\n\nAntagonists are members of Heiwa-Gumi, a Japanese [[yakuza]] gang, though there are a few Caucasian bosses and mid-level bosses (including three wrestling characters, Tom Anderson, Gary Powell and the Mad Dilly, modelled after [[Hulk Hogan]] and [[Randy Savage]]), and the final boss is [[Italians|Italian]] mob boss '''Castella''' (''Casterora'' in [[Japanese language|Japanese]]). Moreover, the game has no individual endings, no matter which character has been chosen. After defeating Castella, players are presented with various scenes of the game along with the credits, and finally a group picture of the main characters.\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n|title     = Contemporary reception\n|GR        = (Neo Geo) 55%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamerankings.com/neo/582031-burning-fight/index.html|title=Burning Fight for NeoGeo|work=[[GameRankings]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=2019|accessdate=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|Allgame   = (Neo Geo) {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"AGNGbf\">{{cite web|last=Knight|first=Kyle|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16994&tab=review|title=Burning Fight (Neo Geo Advanced Entertainment System) - Review|work=[[AllGame]]|publisher=[[All Media Network]]|date=1998|access-date=2019-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115224240/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16994&tab=review|archive-date=2014-11-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|CVG       = (Neo Geo) 92 / 100<ref name=\"CVGNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last1=Rand|first1=Paul|last2=Boone|first2=Tim|url=https://archive.org/stream/computer-video-games-magazine-122/CVG122_Jan_1992#page/n33/mode/2up|title=Reviews - Neo Geo -- Burning Fight|magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]]|issue=122|publisher=[[Future plc|Future Publishing]]|date=January 1992|pages=34\u201335}}</ref>\n|GamePro   = (Neo Geo) 24 / 25<ref name=\"GProNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last=Quan|first=Slasher|url=https://archive.org/details/GamePro_Issue_030_January_1992/page/n103|title=Neo Geo For Real! - Burning Fight|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=30|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=January 1992|pages=101\u2013102}}</ref>\n|rev1      = ''[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]''\n|rev1Score = (Neo Geo) 92%<ref name=\"C+NGbf\">{{cite magazine|author1=Loulou|author2=El Nio Nio|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=8895&album=oui|title=Neo Geo Review - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]|issue=5|publisher=[[:fr:M.E.R.7|M.E.R.7]]|date=January 1992|pages=34\u201335|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev2      = ''[[Hobby Consolas|Hobby Hi-Tech]]''\n|rev2Score = (Neo Geo CD) 4 / 10<ref name=\"HHiTechNGCDbf\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/HiTechMagazine/HiTech%2001#page/n28/mode/1up|title=Reportaje - Cl\u00e1sicos en CD -- Titulos disponibles para el nuevo formato de SNK: Burning Fight|magazine=[[Hobby Consolas|Hobby Hi-Tech]]|issue=1|publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]|date=March 1995|page=29|lang=es}}</ref>\n|rev3      = ''[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]''\n|rev3Score = (Neo Geo) 92%<ref name=\"JpadNGbf\">{{cite magazine|author1=Steph|last2=Demoly|first2=Jean-Marc|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=84&num=1771&album=oui|title=Test - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]|issue=2|publisher=[[:fr:Yellow Media|Yellow Media]]|date=November 1991|pages=122\u2013124|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev4      = ''[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]''\n|rev4Score = (Neo Geo) 92%<ref name=\"JNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last=Demoly|first=Jean-Marc|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Joystick/joystick_numero020/Joystick%20020%20-%20Page%20131%20(1991-10).jpg|title=Tests - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]|issue=20|publisher=[[:fr:Anuman Interactive|Anuman Interactive]]|date=October 1991|page=131|lang=fr|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|rev5      = ''[[:de:Mega Fun|Mega Fun]]''\n|rev5Score = (Neo Geo) 77%<ref name=\"MFNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last1=Noak|first1=Philipp|last2=Hellert|first2=Stefan|url=http://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=8807&s=3|title=Special - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:de:Mega Fun|Mega Fun]]|issue=11|publisher=[[:de:Computec Media Group|CT Computec Verlag GmbH & Co. KG]]|date=August 1993|pages=28\u201330|lang=de|access-date=2019-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021232116/http://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=8807&s=3|archive-date=2018-10-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev6      = ''[[:ja:\u30de\u30a4\u30b3\u30f3BASIC\u30de\u30ac\u30b8\u30f3|Micom BASIC Magazine]]''\n|rev6Score = (Neo Geo) {{Rating|3}}<ref name=\"MBASICMNGbf\">{{cite magazine|author1=Yanma|author2=Itabashi|url=https://archive.org/stream/micomBASIC_1992-07#page/n232/mode/1up|title=Super Soft \u5927\u7279\u96c6 - \u4eca\u3001\u300eNEO\u30fbGEO\u300f\u304c\u304a\u3082\u3057\u308d\u3044\uff01: \u30d0\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30c8|magazine=[[:ja:\u30de\u30a4\u30b3\u30f3BASIC\u30de\u30ac\u30b8\u30f3|Micom BASIC Magazine]]|issue=121|publisher=[[:ja:\u96fb\u6ce2\u65b0\u805e\u793e|The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation]]|date=July 1992|page=209|lang=ja}}</ref>\n|rev7      = ''[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]''\n|rev7Score = (Neo Geo) 85%<ref name=\"PONGbf\">{{cite magazine|last=Drevet|first=Cyril|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=32&num=1063&album=oui|title=Tests De Jeux - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]|issue=16|publisher=[[:fr:M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition|M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition]]|date=January 1992|pages=80\u201381|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev8      = ''[[Sinclair User]]''\n|rev8Score = (Arcade) 74%<ref name=\"SUACbf\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/sinclair-user-magazine-113/SinclairUser_113_Jul_1991#page/n38/mode/1up|title=Coin Ops - Burning Fight \u2022 Neo Geo|magazine=[[Sinclair User]]|issue=113|publisher=[[Ascential|EMAP]]|date=July 1991|page=39}}</ref>\n}}\n\nWhile ''Burning Fight'' was successful critically,<ref name=\"VGNGbf\">{{cite magazine|last=Knauf|first=Andreas|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=5065&s=2|title=News - Neo Geo - Burning Fight|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=5|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=January 1992|pages=10\u201312|lang=de}}</ref> it received a lukewarm welcome by fans of the genre. The lack of popularity led the game to fail to have the impact SNK was hoping for and it was left behind its better known competitors. ''Sinclair User'' highlighted this sense of dullness by giving the game a rating of 74 and stating that, \"Burning Fight is a competent journey along the usual beat-'em-up road...\"<ref name=\"SUACbf\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Retrospective reviews ===\n{{Video game reviews\n|title = Retrospective assessments\n|GR    = (Switch) 30%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamerankings.com/switch/223218-aca-neogeo-burning-fight/index.html|title=ACA NeoGeo: Burning Fight for Nintendo Switch|work=[[GameRankings]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=2019|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|EuroG = (Wii) 7 / 10<ref name=\"EuroGVCbf\">{{cite web|last=Whitehead|first=Dan|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/virtual-console-roundup_8|title=Virtual Console Roundup - Paradroid, Burning Fight, Pokemon Puzzle League and Samurai Shodown|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network Ltd.|date=June 2, 2008|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|IGN   = (Wii) 4.5 / 10<ref name=\"IGNVCbf\">{{cite web|last=M. Thomas|first=Lucas|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2008/07/07/burning-fight-review|title=Burning Fight Review|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=July 7, 2008|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n|NLife = (Wii) 5 / 10<ref name=\"NLifeVCbf\">{{cite web|last=McFerran|first=Damien|url=https://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/neogeo/burning_fight|title=Burning Fight Review (Neo Geo)|work=[[Nintendo Life]]|publisher=Nlife Media|date=May 31, 2008|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref><br />(Switch) 3 / 10<ref name=\"NLifeNSbf\">{{cite web|last=Frear|first=Dave|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/switch-eshop/burning_fight_neogeo|title=Burning Fight Review (Switch eShop / Neo Geo)|work=[[Nintendo Life]]|publisher=Nlife Media|date=October 2, 2017|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Burning Fight'' has been met with a much more mixed reception from critics since its release.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of Neo Geo games]]\n*[[NeoGeo Battle Coliseum]]\n*[[Double Dragon]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/arcade/575702-burning-fight ''Burning Fight''] at [[GameFAQs]]\n* [https://www.giantbomb.com/burning-fight/3030-16610/ ''Burning Fight''] at [[Giant Bomb]]\n* [https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=7242 ''Burning Fight''] at