{"title_page": "Golap Borbora", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = <small>[[List of Chief Ministers of Assam|Ex. Chief Minister of Assam]]</small>\n|name             = Golap Borbora <br> \u0997\u09cb\u09b2\u09be\u09aa \u09ac\u09f0\u09ac\u09f0\u09be \n|honorific-suffix =\n|honorific_suffix = <small>Ex. Chief Minister of Assam</small>\n|image            =Golap Borbora.jpg\n| imagesize=200px\n|office           = [[List of Chief Ministers of Assam|6th Chief Minister of Assam]]<ref name=\"cm-list\">{{cite web|url=http://assamassembly.nic.in/cm-list.html |title=Assam Legislative Assembly - Chief Ministers since 1937 |publisher=Assam Legislative Assembly, Dispur, Guwahati |accessdate=20 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116091830/http://assamassembly.nic.in/cm-list.html |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref>\n| leader = [[Janata Party]]\n|term_start       = 12 March 1978\n|term_end         = 4 September 1979<ref name=\"cm-list\" />\n|predecessor      = [[Sarat Chandra Sinha]]\n|successor        =[[Jogendra Nath Hazarika]]<ref name=\"cm-list\" />\n| office2 =M.L.A., Tinsukia L.A.<ref name=\"mla-1978-83\">{{cite web | url=http://assamassembly.gov.in/mla-1978-83.html | title=Assam Legislative Assembly - MLA 1978-83 | publisher=Assam Legislative Assembly, Dispur, Guwahati | accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n|term_start2      = 1978\n|term_end2        = 1983\n|predecessor2     = Paramananda Gogoi<ref name=\"mla-1972-78\">{{cite web | url=http://assamassembly.gov.in/mla-1972-78.html | title=Assam Legislative Assembly - MLA 1972-78 | publisher=Assam Legislative Assembly, Dispur, Guwahati | accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n| successor2 = Rajendra Nath Phukon<ref name=\"MLA 1983-85\">{{cite web | url=http://assamassembly.gov.in/mla-1983-85.html | title=Assam Legislative Assembly - MLA 1983-85 | publisher=Assam Legislative Assembly, Dispur, Guwahati | accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date|df=y|1926|8|29}}\n|birth_place      = [[Golaghat]], [[Assam Province|Assam]], [[British India]]\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|df=y|2006|3|19|1926|8|29}}\n|death_place      = [[Guwahati]], [[Assam]], [[India]]\n|party            = [[Janata Party]]\n|spouse           = \n|children         =\n|religion         = [[Hinduism]]\n|profession       = Politics\n|University       = \n}}\n'''Golap Borbora''' ({{lang-as|\u0997\u09cb\u09b2\u09be\u09aa \u09ac\u09f0\u09ac\u09f0\u09be}}; 29 August 1926 \u2013 19 March 2006) was a chief minister of Indian state of [[Assam]] from 1978 to 1979. He was the first non congress chief minister of Assam. Borbora was a member of [[Rajya Sabha]] between 1968 and 1974.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born in [[Golaghat]] and had his early schooling in [[Tinsukia]] and then studied at the [[University of Calcutta]]. His parents were Komol Borbora (an executive officer from Indian Oil Corporation Limited, Digboi) and Puniyaprova Borbora. His father later left his job due to official issues (a long strike in the company). He had ten siblings, one of whom was [[Renu Saikia]], who later became famous as a prolific actress in the [[Assamese film industry]].<ref>http://www.nettv4u.com/celebrity/hindi/movie-actress/renu-saikia</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nBorbora was a follower of [[Ram Manohar Lohia]] and [[Jai Prakash Narayan]] and was imprisoned several times during the freedom movement.\n\nIn free India he was arrested in 1975 for opposing [[Indira Gandhi]]'s regime in the emergency in 1975 and spent 18 months in Tihar Jail. Golap Borbora became the State unit president of the [[Janata Party]] in 1977 and  led the party to victory. He was elected the first non-Congress Chief Minister of Assam in 1978.\n\nThe Janata Party Government led by Borbora lasted for 18 months only. However, many think that the government did not last long as he had tried to stop influx of illegal immigrants from neighboring countries and also to demonopolize the liquor trade in tea garden belts. His government exempted land revenue for farmers up to 10 bighas and ordered fee exemptions to school students up to HSLC level and all girls up to high school level. The government also introduced free medical treatment in all the government hospitals and allowed free movement of foods-grains within the state.\n\nHe died in 2006.\n\n==Commemorative efforts==\n\nAs an attempt to commemorate the contributions of Borbora, College Students Welfare Committee, an N.G.O has instituted the C.S.W.C Golap Borbora Scholarship Programme that extends scholarship assistance to meritorious students. The same organisation also hosts the annual C.S.W.C Golap Borbora Memorial Lecture. The organisation is Presided by Mr. Abhinav P Borbora who is the grandson of the former Chief Minister.^^ \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120206233634/http://www.nenanews.com/ANE%20April%201-15,06/oh1.htm Former Assam CM Golap Borbora is no more] North East News Agency, 1\u201315 April 2006\n*[http://www.telegraphindia.com/1060320/asp/frontpage/story_5988798.asp Golap Borbora passes away], The Telegraph,  Monday, 20 March 2006\n^^[https://www.sentinelassam.com/news/scholarship-in-memory-of-golap-borbora/]\n\n{{Chief Ministers of Assam}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borbora, Golap}}\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Assam]]\n[[Category:People from Golaghat district]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta alumni]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Chief ministers from Janata Party]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Assam]]\n[[Category:Janata Dal politicians]]\n[[Category:Janata Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Lok Dal politicians]]\n{{India-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = <small>[[List of Chief Ministers of Assam|Ex. Chief Minister of Assam]]</small>\n|name             = Golap Borbora <br> \u0997\u09cb\u09b2\u09be\u09aa \u09ac\u09f0\u09ac\u09f0\u09be \n|honorific-suffix =\n|honorific_suffix = <small>Ex. Chief Minister of Assam</small>\n|image            =Golap Borbora.jpg\n| imagesize=200px\n|office           = [[List of Chief Ministers of Assam|6th Chief Minister of Assam]]<ref name=\"cm-list\">{{cite web|url=http://assamassembly.nic.in/cm-list.html |title=Assam Legislative Assembly - Chief Ministers since 1937 |publisher=Assam Legislative Assembly, Dispur, Guwahati |accessdate=20 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116091830/http://assamassembly.nic.in/cm-list.html |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref>\n| leader = [[Janata Party]]\n|term_start       = 12 March 1978\n|term_end         = 4 September 1979<ref name=\"cm-list\" />\n|predecessor      = [[Sarat Chandra Sinha]]\n|successor        =[[Jogendra Nath Hazarika]]<ref name=\"cm-list\" />\n| office2 =M.L.A., Tinsukia L.A.<ref name=\"mla-1978-83\">{{cite web | url=http://assamassembly.gov.in/mla-1978-83.html | title=Assam Legislative Assembly - MLA 1978-83 | publisher=Assam Legislative Assembly, Dispur, Guwahati | accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n|term_start2      = 1978\n|term_end2        = 1983\n|predecessor2     = Paramananda Gogoi<ref name=\"mla-1972-78\">{{cite web | url=http://assamassembly.gov.in/mla-1972-78.html | title=Assam Legislative Assembly - MLA 1972-78 | publisher=Assam Legislative Assembly, Dispur, Guwahati | accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n| successor2 = Rajendra Nath Phukon<ref name=\"MLA 1983-85\">{{cite web | url=http://assamassembly.gov.in/mla-1983-85.html | title=Assam Legislative Assembly - MLA 1983-85 | publisher=Assam Legislative Assembly, Dispur, Guwahati | accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref>\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date|df=y|1926|8|29}}\n|birth_place      = [[Golaghat]], [[Assam Province|Assam]], [[British India]]\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|df=y|2006|3|19|1926|8|29}}\n|death_place      = [[Guwahati]], [[Assam]], [[India]]\n|party            = [[Janata Party]]\n|spouse           = \n|children         =\n|religion         = [[Hinduism]]\n|profession       = Politics\n|University       = \n}}\n'''Golap Borbora''' ({{lang-as|\u0997\u09cb\u09b2\u09be\u09aa \u09ac\u09f0\u09ac\u09f0\u09be}}; 29 August 1926 \u2013 19 March 2006) was a chief minister of Indian state of [[Assam]] from 1978 to 1979. He was the first non congress chief minister of Assam. Borbora was a member of [[Rajya Sabha]] between 1968 and 1974.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born in [[Golaghat]] and had his early schooling in [[Tinsukia]] and then studied at the [[University of Calcutta]]. His parents were Komol Borbora (an executive officer from Indian Oil Corporation Limited, Digboi) and Puniyaprova Borbora. His father later left his job due to official issues (a long strike in the company). He had ten siblings, one of whom was [[Renu Saikia]], who later became famous as a prolific actress in the [[Assamese film industry]].<ref>http://www.nettv4u.com/celebrity/hindi/movie-actress/renu-saikia</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nBorbora was a follower of [[Ram Manohar Lohia]] and [[Jai Prakash Narayan]] and was imprisoned several times during the freedom movement.\n\nIn free India he was arrested in 1975 for opposing [[Indira Gandhi]]'s regime in the emergency in 1975 and spent 18 months in Tihar Jail. Golap Borbora became the State unit president of the [[Janata Party]] in 1977 and  led the party to victory. He was elected the first non-Congress Chief Minister of Assam in 1978.\n\nThe Janata Party Government led by Borbora lasted for 18 months only. However, many think that the government did not last long as he had tried to stop influx of illegal immigrants from neighboring countries and also to demonopolize the liquor trade in tea garden belts. His government exempted land revenue for farmers up to 10 bighas and ordered fee exemptions to school students up to HSLC level and all girls up to high school level. The government also introduced free medical treatment in all the government hospitals and allowed free movement of foods-grains within the state.\n\nHe died in 2006.\n\n==Commemorative efforts==\n\nAs an attempt to commemorate the contributions of Borbora, College Students Welfare Committee, an N.G.O has instituted the C.S.W.C Golap Borbora Scholarship Programme that extends scholarship assistance to meritorious students. The same organisation also hosts the annual C.S.W.C Golap Borbora Memorial Lecture. The organisation is Presided by Mr. Abhinav P Borbora who is the grandson of the former Chief Minister.^^ \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120206233634/http://www.nenanews.com/ANE%20April%201-15,06/oh1.htm Former Assam CM Golap Borbora is no more] North East News Agency, 1\u201315 April 2006\n*[http://www.telegraphindia.com/1060320/asp/frontpage/story_5988798.asp Golap Borbora passes away], The Telegraph,  Monday, 20 March 2006\n^^[https://www.sentinelassam.com/news/scholarship-in-memory-of-golap-borbora/]\n\n{{Chief Ministers of Assam}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borbora, Golap}}\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Assam]]\n[[Category:People from Golaghat district]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta alumni]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Chief ministers from Janata Party]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Assam]]\n\n\n{{India-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jaywardhan009", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golap_Borbora"}
