{"title_page": "Yaakov Perlow", "text_new": "{{short description|American rabbi}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Jewish leader \n| honorific-prefix = Grand Rabbi\n| name             = Rav Yaakov Perlow\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)|Novominsker]] [[Rebbe]]\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| synagogue        = \n| synagogueposition = \n| yeshiva          = Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda\n| yeshivaposition  = [[Rosh yeshiva]]\n| organisation     = [[Agudath Israel of America]]\n| organisationposition = President\n| began            = December 1998\n| ended            = \n| predecessor      = Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]]\n| successor        = \n| rabbi            = \n| rebbe            = \n| kohan            = \n| hazzan           = \n| rank             = \n| other_post       = Head of [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages)\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date       = 1931\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], New York\n| death_date       = {{death date and given age|2020|4|7|89}} \n| death_place      = Brooklyn, New York\n| yahrtzeit        = \n| buried           = \n| nationality      = United States\n| denomination     = \n| residence        = \n| dynasty          = [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)]]\n| parents          = \n| father           = Rabbi Nochum Mordechai Perlow\n| mother           = Beila Rochma Morgenstern\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| alma_mater       = [[Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin]]<br>[[Beth Medrash Govoha]]\n| semicha          = \n}}\n'''Yaakov Perlow''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05e4\u05e8\u05dc\u05d5\u05d1}}, 1931 &nbsp;\u2013 April 7, 2020) was an American [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] rabbi and [[rosh yeshiva]], and [[Rebbe]] of the [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)|Novominsker]] [[List of Hasidic dynasties|Hasidic dynasty]]. From 1998 until his death, he was president of [[Agudath Israel of America]], a [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] advocacy organization. He was also head of that organization's [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages). He was one of the most respected leaders of the American Orthodox Jewish community, known for his scholarly and oratorical skills.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nYaakov Perlow was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York, to Rabbi Nochum Mordechai Perlow (1887\u20131976), the Novominsker Rebbe, and his wife, Beila Rochma Morgenstern.<ref name=\"matzav\">{{cite web|url=http://matzav.com/todays-yahrtzeits-and-history-9-elul-2/|title=Today's Yahrtzeits and History \u2013 9 Elul|date=August 24, 2015|publisher=matzav.com|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> He was named after his paternal grandfather, the founder of the Novominsk Hasidic dynasty.<ref name=bhol>{{cite web |url=https://www.bhol.co.il/news/1092156|title=\u05d0\u05d1\u05dc \u05d1\u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d7\u05e8\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea: \u05d4\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9 \u05de\u05e0\u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05e1\u05e7 \u05d6\u05e6\"\u05dc \u05e8\u05d0\u05e9 \u05d0\u05d2\u05d5\"\u05d9 \u05d1\u05d0\u05de\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4 |language=Hebrew|trans-title=Mourning in Haredi Judaism: The Novominsker Rebbe, zt'l, Head of Agudath Israel in America|first=Moshe|last=Weisberg|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=Behadrei Chareidim}}</ref> His maternal grandfather was Rabbi [[Yitzchak Zelig Morgenstern]], the Sokolover Rebbe, a direct descendant of Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel of Kotzk]].<ref name=bhol/><ref name=\"pol\">{{cite web|url=http://poznan.jewish.org.pl/index.php/portrety/Zapomniany-rabin.html|title=Zapomniany rabin|last=Markusz|first=Katarzyna|publisher=poznan.jewish.org.pl|language=Polish|trans-title=Forgotten Rabbi|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> Morgenstern was one of the main founders of [[World Agudath Israel|Agudath Israel]] in Poland.<ref name=\"matzav\" /><ref name=\"new\" />\n\nPerlow began his Torah education at Yeshiva Toras Chaim in [[East New York]], and continued on to the [[Lithuanian Jews|Lithuanian]]-type yeshivas of Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin in Brooklyn and [[Beth Medrash Govoha]] in [[Lakewood Township, New Jersey|Lakewood]], New Jersey.<ref name=steve>{{cite web|url=https://web.stevens.edu/golem/llevine/ry_interviews/Interviews%20with%20RYs.pdf|title=Interviews conducted by Professor William Helmreich with various Roshei Yeshiva Helmreich with various Roshei Yeshiva |publisher=Stevens Institute of Technology|date=December 28, 1977|accessdate=August 25, 2016|pages=10\u201320}}</ref>{{sfn|Helmreich|2000|p=369}} He also graduated with honors from [[Brooklyn College]].{{sfn|Helmreich|2000|p=369}}{{sfn|Heilman|1995|p=326}}\n\n== Career ==\nPerlow subsequently taught at [[Hebrew Theological College]] in [[Skokie, Illinois]].<ref name=\"steve\" /> From there, he was appointed [[rosh yeshiva]] at the Breuer's yeshiva, Yeshiva Rabbi Samson Refael Hirsch, in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]], New York.<ref name=\"kaj\">{{cite web |url= http://www.kajinc.org/about/history|title= The Kehilla \u2013 A Brief Historical Overview|publisher=[[K'hal Adath Jeshurun]]|year=2016|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> After the death of his father, he began serving as Novominsker Rebbe. He established the Novominsk Hasidic Center and founded his own yeshiva, Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda, in [[Borough Park, Brooklyn]].<ref name=bhol/>\n\n===Agudath Israel of America===\nIn December 1998, Perlow was named president of the [[Agudath Israel of America]] organization, succeeding Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]], who had died seven months earlier.<ref name=\"new\">{{cite web |url= https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22213037.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195646/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22213037.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= October 8, 2016|title= Novominsker Rebbe Emerges as New Sage of Aguda: Perlow Assumes Mantle|work=The Forward|date=December 4, 1998|accessdate=August 25, 2016|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research|HighBeam]]}}</ref> With his appointment, the presidential and leadership duties held by Sherer were divided between Perlow, the new president, and a three-man executive.<ref name=\"new\" /> Perlow was also head of the organization's [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages).<ref name=inn>{{cite web |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/278434|title=US Agudath Yisroel head, Rabbi Yaakov Perlow, the Novominsker Rebbe, dies of coronavirus|first=Mordechai|last=Sones|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=[[Arutz Sheva|Israel National News]]}}</ref>\n\nPerlow frequently spoke out on issues affecting the American Orthodox Jewish world, including Internet usage,<ref name=\"oren\">{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-89108880.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195841/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-89108880.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title=In Other Words|work=[[The Forward]]|first=Oren|last=Rawls|date=December 5, 2003|accessdate=August 25, 2016|quote='The Internet, with the flick of a button, invades a Jewish home, a Jewish soul, and makes moral disaster. And it is happening all the time', warns the highly-respected Rabbi Yaakov Perlow in The Jewish Observer, the house organ of the organization he heads, Agudath Israel of America.}}</ref> child abuse,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yated.com/call-to-action/ |title=Call to Action|work=[[Yated Ne'eman (United States)|Yated Ne'eman]]|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016|quote=The Novominsker Rebbe, Rav Yaakov Perlow, issued a call for action in response to the festering scourge of child abuse and molestation.}}</ref> [[Holocaust denial]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/novominsker-rebbe-condemns-holocaust-comments-of-rabbi-on-video-publicized-by-matzav-com/|title=Novominsker Rebbe Condemns Holocaust Comments of Rabbi on Video Publicized by Matzav.com|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016|publisher=matzav.com|first=Gavriel |last=Sitrit|quote=I condemn in the strongest terms possible the outrageous claim that fewer than a million halachic Jews were killed in the Holocaust.}}</ref> overpriced Jewish weddings,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79394097.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195810/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79394097.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title= Waiter, Hold The Knishes: Agudah urges cutting back on pricey weddings|first=Debra Nussbaum|last=Cohen|date=December 7, 2001|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[The Jewish Week]]|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam|quote=These rabbis, led by Yaakov Perlow, the chief religious authority of the fervently Orthodox organization Agudath Israel of America, are leading a charge to change the communal culture around frum weddings, where even families of moderate means feel social pressure to invite upward of 1,000 people and serve them food from lavish smorgasbords set with everything from intricate ice sculptures to glatt kosher prime rib carving stations.}}</ref> and U.S. politics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-102216388.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195626/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-102216388.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |title=Senator Presses for 2004, Before Focusing on Own Ambition|first=Joshua|last=Runyan|date=September 9, 2004|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=The Jewish Exponent|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam|quote=[Rick] Santorum and first-term Sen. Norm Coleman (R-Minn.) sat with Orthodox leaders during a closed-door meeting at Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda. After the meeting, Santorum said that he took to heart a message delivered to him by the Novominsker Rebbe, Rabbi Yaakov Perlow, and that he would try to incorporate that message into his convention address. \"I won't have time to mention my visit, but I will have the time to transmit the words of the rebbe upstairs, the importance of faith communities and making sure those communities can transmit their faith\", he said.}}</ref> In 2015, Perlow shocked attendees at the 93rd annual Agudath Israel of America dinner by directly appealing to [[Barack Obama|President Obama]] to reconsider the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|Iran deal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/309218/photos-novominsker-rebbe-issues-direct-plea-to-president-obama-at-agudath-israel-dinner.html|title= Novominsker Rebbe Issues Direct Plea to President Obama at Agudath Israel Dinner |date=May 12, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref>\n\nPerlow was seen as a controversial figure by some non-Orthodox Jewish groups in light of his comments about [[heterodoxy|heterodox]] Jewish movements. While he consistently called for increased dialogue and rapprochement with non-Orthodox Jews, he coupled that with condemnation of the non-Orthodox movements themselves. At the 73rd annual Agudah convention in 1995, he urged dialogue with non-Orthodox Jews while at the same time \"lashing out at what he described as the 'false ideology' of non-Orthodox Judaism.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.jta.org/1995/11/28/archive/agudath-israel-leader-calls-for-dialogue-as-he-lashes-out |title= Agudath Israel Leader Calls for Dialogue As He Lashes Out|date=November 28, 1995|accessdate=August 26, 2016|publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]]}}</ref> In June 1999, he wrote in ''[[The Jewish Observer]]'' in support of a rapprochement in the long-standing feud between the Haredi and Reform movements.{{sfn|Ferziger|2015|pp=136\u2013139}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22426699.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195701/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22426699.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title=Perlow's Progress|work=The Forward|date=January 8, 1999|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam}}</ref> At the May 2014 Agudath dinner, he stated that the Reform and Conservative movements \"have disintegrated themselves, become oblivious, fallen into an abyss of intermarriage and assimilation\",<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/rabbis-round-table/.premium-1.597797|title= Fair Criticism, Flawed Justification: Where Rabbi Perlow Went Wrong|first=Dr. Samuel|last=Lebens|date=June 9, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref> and branded another movement, [[Open Orthodoxy]], as being \"steeped in apikorsos\" (heresy).<ref name=\"ny\">{{cite web |url= http://forward.com/news/199010/orthodox-rabbi-stuns-agudath-gala-with-heresy-atta/|title= Orthodox Rabbi Stuns Agudath Gala With 'Heresy' Attack on Open Orthodoxy|first=Josh|last=Nathan-Kazis|date=May 28, 2014|accessdate=August 25, 2016|work=The Forward}}</ref> While New York City Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] was the next speaker at the dinner, he did not challenge Perlow's remarks, which cast aspersions on the affiliations of the non-Orthodox Jewish population of New York City.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/29/nyregion/at-a-jewish-gala-de-blasio-skips-his-cue-to-speak-out.html?_r=0|title=At a Jewish Gala, de Blasio Skips His Cue to Speak Out|first=Michael|last=Powell|date=May 28, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://observer.com/2014/05/bill-de-blasio-furiously-refuses-to-denounce-rabbi-tirade/|title= Bill de Blasio Furiously Refuses to Denounce Rabbi Tirade|first=Ross|last=Barkan|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[New York Observer]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Perlow urged American Orthodox Jews to follow [[social distancing]] and other precautionary guidelines in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus outbreak]], saying: \"We cannot behave the way we did last week or two weeks ago. We're told that the [[halakha]] (Jewish law) is that we must listen to doctors, whether it's about a sick person or [[Yom Kippur]]\".<ref name=inn/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/in-the-eye-of-nys-coronavirus-storm-ultra-orthodox-face-rising-anti-semitism/|title=In the eye of NY's coronavirus storm, ultra-Orthodox face rising anti-Semitism|first=Cathryn J.|last=Prince|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]}}</ref> He was later itself infected by [[COVID-19]] and on April 7, 2020, he died due to complications from that. He was 89.<ref name=bhol/><ref>{{cite news |title=Agudath Israel leader succumbs to coronavirus |url=https://jewishinsider.com/2020/04/agudath-israel-leader-succumbs-to-coronavirus/ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |agency=jewishinsider.com}}</ref> His funeral was held in a private ceremony, with eulogies and the saying of [[Psalm]]s broadcast live via telephone, in order to limit the spread of the virus.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Personal life==\nPerlow's wife Yehudis is the daughter of Grand Rabbi Avrohom Eichenstein of [[Zidichov (Hasidic dynasty)|Zidichov]]-Chicago.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/%D7%A1%D7%A4%D7%A8_%D7%A2%D7%93%D7%AA_%D7%99%D7%A2%D7%A7%D7%91.html?id=T3xGwwEACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=\u05e1\u05e4\u05e8 \u05e2\u05d3\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1: \u05d7\u05d9\u05d3\u05d5\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05d4\u05e2\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05d1\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9 \u05e1\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05e9\u05de\u05e2\u05ea\u05ea\u05d0 \u05d3\u05ea\u05dc\u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d0 \u05d5\u05d1\u05d3\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9 \u05d4\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd|language=Hebrew|trans-title=Sefer Adat Yaakov: Novellae, Annotations and Commentary on Topics in the Talmud and the Works of the Rishonim|year=1982}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/%D7%A2%D7%93%D7%AA_%D7%99%D7%A2%D7%A7%D7%91.html?id=v0XumgEACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=\u05e2\u05d3\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1: \u05dc\u05d7\u05d2 \u05d4\u05e4\u05e1\u05d7|language=Hebrew|trans-title=Adat Yaakov on the Festival of Passover|year=2013}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/%D7%A1%D7%A4%D7%A8_%D7%A2%D7%93%D7%AA_%D7%99%D7%A2%D7%A7%D7%91_%D7%9C%D7%97%D7%92_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%95%D7%A2.html?id=0NE2nQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=\u05e1\u05e4\u05e8 \u05e2\u05d3\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05dc\u05d7\u05d2 \u05d4\u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e2\u05d5\u05ea|language=Hebrew|trans-title=Sefer Adat Yaakov on the Festival of Shavuot|year=2015}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y1RQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 |title=Beyond Sectarianism: The Realignment of American Orthodox Judaism|first=Adam S.|last=Ferziger|year=2015|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=0814339549}}\n*{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GxwUCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA326|title=The Americanization of the Jews|chapter=The Ninth Siyum HaShas: A Case Study in Orthodox Contra-Acculturation|first=Samuel C.|authorlink=Samuel Heilman|last=Heilman|editor-first=Robert|editor-last=Seltzer|year=1995|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=0814780008|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/americanizationo0000unse_f9c0}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lFvQ79N9vIAC&pg=PA369 |title=The World of the Yeshiva: An Intimate Portrait of Orthodox Jewry|first=William B.|last=Helmreich|year=2000|publisher=KTAV Publishing House, Inc.|isbn=0881256420}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161008194128/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A2-8005ae5ca5e54a37a22fd6bab64c8943.html Photo of Rabbi Yaakov Perlow] at the [[Siyum HaShas#12th Siyum HaShas|12th Siyum HaShas]], August 2, 2012\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tM0GUFylNKs \u201cCity Council candidate John Heyer meets with Rabbi Yaakov Perlow and Rabbi Shmuel Lefkowitz\u201d (video)] September 4, 2009\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perlow, Yaakov}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rebbes]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rosh yeshivas]]\n[[Category:American Hasidic rabbis]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]]\n[[Category:Writers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:20th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:21st-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rabbi}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Jewish leader \n| honorific-prefix = Grand Rabbi\n| name             = Rav Yaakov Perlow\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)|Novominsker]] [[Rebbe]]\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| synagogue        = \n| synagogueposition = \n| yeshiva          = Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda\n| yeshivaposition  = [[Rosh yeshiva]]\n| organisation     = [[Agudath Israel of America]]\n| organisationposition = President\n| began            = December 1998\n| ended            = \n| predecessor      = Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]]\n| successor        = \n| rabbi            = \n| rebbe            = \n| kohan            = \n| hazzan           = \n| rank             = \n| other_post       = Head of [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages)\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date       = 1931\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], New York\n| death_date       = {{death date and given age|2020|4|7|89}} \n| death_place      = Brooklyn, New York\n| yahrtzeit        = \n| buried           = \n| nationality      = United States\n| denomination     = \n| residence        = \n| dynasty          = [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)]]\n| parents          = \n| father           = Rabbi Nochum Mordechai Perlow\n| mother           = Beila Rochma Morgenstern\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| alma_mater       = [[Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin]]<br>[[Beth Medrash Govoha]]\n| semicha          = \n}}\n'''Yaakov Perlow''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05e4\u05e8\u05dc\u05d5\u05d1}}, 1931 \u2013 April 7, 2020) was an American [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] rabbi and [[rosh yeshiva]], and [[Rebbe]] of the [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)|Novominsker]] [[List of Hasidic dynasties|Hasidic dynasty]]. From 1998 until his death, he was president of [[Agudath Israel of America]], a [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] advocacy organization. He was also head of that organization's [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages). He was one of the most respected leaders of the American Orthodox Jewish community, known for his scholarly and oratorical skills.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nYaakov Perlow was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York, to Rabbi Nochum Mordechai Perlow (1887\u20131976), the Novominsker Rebbe, and his wife, Beila Rochma Morgenstern.<ref name=\"matzav\">{{cite web|url=http://matzav.com/todays-yahrtzeits-and-history-9-elul-2/|title=Today's Yahrtzeits and History \u2013 9 Elul|date=August 24, 2015|publisher=matzav.com|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> He was named after his paternal grandfather, the founder of the Novominsk Hasidic dynasty.<ref name=bhol>{{cite web |url=https://www.bhol.co.il/news/1092156|title=\u05d0\u05d1\u05dc \u05d1\u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d7\u05e8\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea: \u05d4\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9 \u05de\u05e0\u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05e1\u05e7 \u05d6\u05e6\"\u05dc \u05e8\u05d0\u05e9 \u05d0\u05d2\u05d5\"\u05d9 \u05d1\u05d0\u05de\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4 |language=Hebrew|trans-title=Mourning in Haredi Judaism: The Novominsker Rebbe, zt'l, Head of Agudath Israel in America|first=Moshe|last=Weisberg|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=Behadrei Chareidim}}</ref> His maternal grandfather was Rabbi [[Yitzchak Zelig Morgenstern]], the Sokolover Rebbe, a direct descendant of Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel of Kotzk]].<ref name=bhol/><ref name=\"pol\">{{cite web|url=http://poznan.jewish.org.pl/index.php/portrety/Zapomniany-rabin.html|title=Zapomniany rabin|last=Markusz|first=Katarzyna|publisher=poznan.jewish.org.pl|language=Polish|trans-title=Forgotten Rabbi|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> Morgenstern was one of the main founders of [[World Agudath Israel|Agudath Israel]] in Poland.<ref name=\"matzav\" /><ref name=\"new\" />\n\nPerlow began his Torah education at Yeshiva Toras Chaim in [[East New York]], and continued on to the [[Lithuanian Jews|Lithuanian]]-type yeshivas of Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin in Brooklyn and [[Beth Medrash Govoha]] in [[Lakewood Township, New Jersey|Lakewood]], New Jersey.<ref name=steve>{{cite web|url=https://web.stevens.edu/golem/llevine/ry_interviews/Interviews%20with%20RYs.pdf|title=Interviews conducted by Professor William Helmreich with various Roshei Yeshiva Helmreich with various Roshei Yeshiva |publisher=Stevens Institute of Technology|date=December 28, 1977|accessdate=August 25, 2016|pages=10\u201320}}</ref>{{sfn|Helmreich|2000|p=369}} He also graduated with honors from [[Brooklyn College]].{{sfn|Helmreich|2000|p=369}}{{sfn|Heilman|1995|p=326}}\n\n== Career ==\nPerlow subsequently taught at [[Hebrew Theological College]] in [[Skokie, Illinois]].<ref name=\"steve\" /> From there, he was appointed [[rosh yeshiva]] at the Breuer's yeshiva, Yeshiva Rabbi Samson Refael Hirsch, in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]], New York.<ref name=\"kaj\">{{cite web |url= http://www.kajinc.org/about/history|title= The Kehilla \u2013 A Brief Historical Overview|publisher=[[K'hal Adath Jeshurun]]|year=2016|accessdate=August 25, 2016}}</ref> After the death of his father, he began serving as Novominsker Rebbe. He established the Novominsk Hasidic Center and founded his own yeshiva, Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda, in [[Borough Park, Brooklyn]].<ref name=bhol/>\n\n===Agudath Israel of America===\nIn December 1998, Perlow was named president of the [[Agudath Israel of America]] organization, succeeding Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]], who had died seven months earlier.<ref name=\"new\">{{cite web |url= https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22213037.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195646/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22213037.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= October 8, 2016|title= Novominsker Rebbe Emerges as New Sage of Aguda: Perlow Assumes Mantle|work=The Forward|date=December 4, 1998|accessdate=August 25, 2016|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research|HighBeam]]}}</ref> With his appointment, the presidential and leadership duties held by Sherer were divided between Perlow, the new president, and a three-man executive.<ref name=\"new\" /> Perlow was also head of the organization's [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] (Council of Torah Sages).<ref name=inn>{{cite web |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/278434|title=US Agudath Yisroel head, Rabbi Yaakov Perlow, the Novominsker Rebbe, dies of coronavirus|first=Mordechai|last=Sones|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=[[Arutz Sheva|Israel National News]]}}</ref>\n\nPerlow frequently spoke out on issues affecting the American Orthodox Jewish world, including Internet usage,<ref name=\"oren\">{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-89108880.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195841/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-89108880.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title=In Other Words|work=[[The Forward]]|first=Oren|last=Rawls|date=December 5, 2003|accessdate=August 25, 2016|quote='The Internet, with the flick of a button, invades a Jewish home, a Jewish soul, and makes moral disaster. And it is happening all the time', warns the highly-respected Rabbi Yaakov Perlow in The Jewish Observer, the house organ of the organization he heads, Agudath Israel of America.}}</ref> child abuse,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yated.com/call-to-action/ |title=Call to Action|work=[[Yated Ne'eman (United States)|Yated Ne'eman]]|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016|quote=The Novominsker Rebbe, Rav Yaakov Perlow, issued a call for action in response to the festering scourge of child abuse and molestation.}}</ref> [[Holocaust denial]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/novominsker-rebbe-condemns-holocaust-comments-of-rabbi-on-video-publicized-by-matzav-com/|title=Novominsker Rebbe Condemns Holocaust Comments of Rabbi on Video Publicized by Matzav.com|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016|publisher=matzav.com|first=Gavriel |last=Sitrit|quote=I condemn in the strongest terms possible the outrageous claim that fewer than a million halachic Jews were killed in the Holocaust.}}</ref> overpriced Jewish weddings,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79394097.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195810/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-79394097.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title= Waiter, Hold The Knishes: Agudah urges cutting back on pricey weddings|first=Debra Nussbaum|last=Cohen|date=December 7, 2001|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[The Jewish Week]]|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam|quote=These rabbis, led by Yaakov Perlow, the chief religious authority of the fervently Orthodox organization Agudath Israel of America, are leading a charge to change the communal culture around frum weddings, where even families of moderate means feel social pressure to invite upward of 1,000 people and serve them food from lavish smorgasbords set with everything from intricate ice sculptures to glatt kosher prime rib carving stations.}}</ref> and U.S. politics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-102216388.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195626/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-102216388.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |title=Senator Presses for 2004, Before Focusing on Own Ambition|first=Joshua|last=Runyan|date=September 9, 2004|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=The Jewish Exponent|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam|quote=[Rick] Santorum and first-term Sen. Norm Coleman (R-Minn.) sat with Orthodox leaders during a closed-door meeting at Yeshivas Novominsk Kol Yehuda. After the meeting, Santorum said that he took to heart a message delivered to him by the Novominsker Rebbe, Rabbi Yaakov Perlow, and that he would try to incorporate that message into his convention address. \"I won't have time to mention my visit, but I will have the time to transmit the words of the rebbe upstairs, the importance of faith communities and making sure those communities can transmit their faith\", he said.}}</ref> In 2015, Perlow shocked attendees at the 93rd annual Agudath Israel of America dinner by directly appealing to [[Barack Obama|President Obama]] to reconsider the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|Iran deal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/309218/photos-novominsker-rebbe-issues-direct-plea-to-president-obama-at-agudath-israel-dinner.html|title= Novominsker Rebbe Issues Direct Plea to President Obama at Agudath Israel Dinner |date=May 12, 2015|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref>\n\nPerlow was seen as a controversial figure by some non-Orthodox Jewish groups in light of his comments about [[heterodoxy|heterodox]] Jewish movements. While he consistently called for increased dialogue and rapprochement with non-Orthodox Jews, he coupled that with condemnation of the non-Orthodox movements themselves. At the 73rd annual Agudah convention in 1995, he urged dialogue with non-Orthodox Jews while at the same time \"lashing out at what he described as the 'false ideology' of non-Orthodox Judaism.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.jta.org/1995/11/28/archive/agudath-israel-leader-calls-for-dialogue-as-he-lashes-out |title= Agudath Israel Leader Calls for Dialogue As He Lashes Out|date=November 28, 1995|accessdate=August 26, 2016|publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]]}}</ref> In June 1999, he wrote in ''[[The Jewish Observer]]'' in support of a rapprochement in the long-standing feud between the Haredi and Reform movements.{{sfn|Ferziger|2015|pp=136\u2013139}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22426699.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008195701/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22426699.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 8, 2016|title=Perlow's Progress|work=The Forward|date=January 8, 1999|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam}}</ref> At the May 2014 Agudath dinner, he stated that the Reform and Conservative movements \"have disintegrated themselves, become oblivious, fallen into an abyss of intermarriage and assimilation\",<ref name=\"nyt\" /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/rabbis-round-table/.premium-1.597797|title= Fair Criticism, Flawed Justification: Where Rabbi Perlow Went Wrong|first=Dr. Samuel|last=Lebens|date=June 9, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref> and branded another movement, [[Open Orthodoxy]], as being \"steeped in apikorsos\" (heresy).<ref name=\"ny\">{{cite web |url= http://forward.com/news/199010/orthodox-rabbi-stuns-agudath-gala-with-heresy-atta/|title= Orthodox Rabbi Stuns Agudath Gala With 'Heresy' Attack on Open Orthodoxy|first=Josh|last=Nathan-Kazis|date=May 28, 2014|accessdate=August 25, 2016|work=The Forward}}</ref> While New York City Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] was the next speaker at the dinner, he did not challenge Perlow's remarks, which cast aspersions on the affiliations of the non-Orthodox Jewish population of New York City.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/29/nyregion/at-a-jewish-gala-de-blasio-skips-his-cue-to-speak-out.html?_r=0|title=At a Jewish Gala, de Blasio Skips His Cue to Speak Out|first=Michael|last=Powell|date=May 28, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://observer.com/2014/05/bill-de-blasio-furiously-refuses-to-denounce-rabbi-tirade/|title= Bill de Blasio Furiously Refuses to Denounce Rabbi Tirade|first=Ross|last=Barkan|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016|work=[[New York Observer]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Perlow urged American Orthodox Jews to follow [[social distancing]] and other precautionary guidelines in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus outbreak]], saying: \"We cannot behave the way we did last week or two weeks ago. We're told that the [[halakha]] (Jewish law) is that we must listen to doctors, whether it's about a sick person or [[Yom Kippur]]\".<ref name=inn/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/in-the-eye-of-nys-coronavirus-storm-ultra-orthodox-face-rising-anti-semitism/|title=In the eye of NY's coronavirus storm, ultra-Orthodox face rising anti-Semitism|first=Cathryn J.|last=Prince|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|work=[[The Times of Israel]]}}</ref> He was later itself infected by [[COVID-19]] and on April 7, 2020, he died due to complications from that. He was 89.<ref name=bhol/><ref>{{cite news |title=Agudath Israel leader succumbs to coronavirus |url=https://jewishinsider.com/2020/04/agudath-israel-leader-succumbs-to-coronavirus/ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |agency=jewishinsider.com}}</ref> His funeral was held in a private ceremony, with eulogies and the saying of [[Psalm]]s broadcast live via telephone, in order to limit the spread of the virus.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Personal life==\nPerlow's wife Yehudis is the daughter of Grand Rabbi Avrohom Eichenstein of [[Zidichov (Hasidic dynasty)|Zidichov]]-Chicago.<ref name=bhol/>\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/%D7%A1%D7%A4%D7%A8_%D7%A2%D7%93%D7%AA_%D7%99%D7%A2%D7%A7%D7%91.html?id=T3xGwwEACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=\u05e1\u05e4\u05e8 \u05e2\u05d3\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1: \u05d7\u05d9\u05d3\u05d5\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05d4\u05e2\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05d1\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9 \u05e1\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05e9\u05de\u05e2\u05ea\u05ea\u05d0 \u05d3\u05ea\u05dc\u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d0 \u05d5\u05d1\u05d3\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9 \u05d4\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd|language=Hebrew|trans-title=Sefer Adat Yaakov: Novellae, Annotations and Commentary on Topics in the Talmud and the Works of the Rishonim|year=1982}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/%D7%A2%D7%93%D7%AA_%D7%99%D7%A2%D7%A7%D7%91.html?id=v0XumgEACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=\u05e2\u05d3\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1: \u05dc\u05d7\u05d2 \u05d4\u05e4\u05e1\u05d7|language=Hebrew|trans-title=Adat Yaakov on the Festival of Passover|year=2013}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/%D7%A1%D7%A4%D7%A8_%D7%A2%D7%93%D7%AA_%D7%99%D7%A2%D7%A7%D7%91_%D7%9C%D7%97%D7%92_%D7%94%D7%A9%D7%91%D7%95%D7%A2.html?id=0NE2nQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=\u05e1\u05e4\u05e8 \u05e2\u05d3\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05dc\u05d7\u05d2 \u05d4\u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e2\u05d5\u05ea|language=Hebrew|trans-title=Sefer Adat Yaakov on the Festival of Shavuot|year=2015}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y1RQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 |title=Beyond Sectarianism: The Realignment of American Orthodox Judaism|first=Adam S.|last=Ferziger|year=2015|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=0814339549}}\n*{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GxwUCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA326|title=The Americanization of the Jews|chapter=The Ninth Siyum HaShas: A Case Study in Orthodox Contra-Acculturation|first=Samuel C.|authorlink=Samuel Heilman|last=Heilman|editor-first=Robert|editor-last=Seltzer|year=1995|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=0814780008|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/americanizationo0000unse_f9c0}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lFvQ79N9vIAC&pg=PA369 |title=The World of the Yeshiva: An Intimate Portrait of Orthodox Jewry|first=William B.|last=Helmreich|year=2000|publisher=KTAV Publishing House, Inc.|isbn=0881256420}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161008194128/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A2-8005ae5ca5e54a37a22fd6bab64c8943.html Photo of Rabbi Yaakov Perlow] at the [[Siyum HaShas#12th Siyum HaShas|12th Siyum HaShas]], August 2, 2012\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tM0GUFylNKs \u201cCity Council candidate John Heyer meets with Rabbi Yaakov Perlow and Rabbi Shmuel Lefkowitz\u201d (video)] September 4, 2009\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perlow, Yaakov}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rebbes]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rosh yeshivas]]\n[[Category:American Hasidic rabbis]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]]\n[[Category:Writers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:20th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:21st-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edit and clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yaakov_Perlow"}
{"title_page": "Ford Australia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Ford Motor Company of Australia Limited\n| logo = Ford_logo_flat.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| type = Subsidiary of [[Ford Motor Company]] of the United States\n| industry = [[Automotive]]\n| foundation = 1925\n| founder = [[Henry Ford]]\n| location = [[Richmond, Victoria|Richmond, Melbourne]] (Head Office)<br>[[Campbellfield, Victoria|Campbellfield, Melbourne]] (Asia Pacific Engineering Centre)\n| key_people = Kay Hart, CEO\n| num_employees = 1300<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ford.com.au/aboutfordaustralia |title=About Ford \u2013 Australia |publisher=Ford Australia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052609/http://www.ford.com.au/aboutfordaustralia |archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.ford.com.au}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Ford norlane.jpg|right|thumb|Ford factory in [[Norlane, Victoria]], 1957.]]\n\nThe '''Ford Motor Company of Australia Limited''', known by its trading name '''Ford Australia''', is the Australian subsidiary of [[Automotive industry in the United States|United States-based automaker]] [[Ford Motor Company]]. It was founded in [[Geelong]], Victoria, in 1925 as an outpost of [[Ford Motor Company of Canada, Limited]]. At that time, Ford Canada was a separate company from Ford USA. [[Henry Ford]] had granted the manufacturing rights of Ford motor vehicles in the British Empire (later the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]]), except the United Kingdom, to Canadian investors.\n\nFord Australia's first products were Model Ts assembled from [[Complete knock down|complete knock-down (CKD) kits]] provided by Ford of Canada. It is best known in more recent times for having produced the [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Falcon]], originally a US model introduced in Australia in 1960, but adapted to Australian requirements and road conditions.\n\nDONT BUY A FORD!!!!!!\nOUR FORD MONDEO 88000 KLM AND IM TOLD TOUGH !!THAT OUR TRANMISSION THAT HAS FAILED IS BAD LUCK... FORD  YOUR A DISGRACE.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:TModel launch Geelong.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ford Model T]] parked outside the [[Geelong]] Library at its launch in Australia in 1925]]\n[[File:Ford geelong construction.jpg|thumb|right|The Ford Australia plant under construction in [[Geelong]], 1926.]]\n\nOn 31 March 1925, Ford announced that [[Geelong]], was to be the Australian headquarters. The first Australian-built Ford was a [[Ford Model T|Model T]] that came off an improvised production line in a disused Geelong wool storage warehouse in June 1925, while work started on a factory in the nearby suburb of Norlane. In 1928 the factory switched to the [[Ford Model A (1927)|Model A]] and was followed by the [[1932 Ford|Ford V8]] in 1932.<ref name=gex150>{{cite book | author = Peter Begg | title = Geelong \u2013 The First 150 Years | publisher = Globe Press | year = 1990 | isbn = 0-9592863-5-7 | page = }}</ref>\n\nIn 1934, the company released a [[coupe utility]] based upon the Model A American Ford \"Closed Cab Pickup Truck\" that had been produced for 6 years from 1928. The local designer was Ford engineer [[Lewis Bandt|Louis (Lewis) Bandt]].<ref name=gex150 /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/bandt-louis-thornett-lewis-12169/text21807|title=Bandt, Louis Thornett (Lewis) (1910\u20131987)  |author=Damian Veltri |publisher= [[Australian Dictionary of Biography]], National Centre of Biography, [[Australian National University]] |accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> During the [[Great Depression]], banks would not extend credit to farmers to purchase passenger cars- in the belief they were unnecessary luxuries. However, they would lend money for the purchase of \"working\" vehicles. The coupe utility fulfilled the need of farmers to have a workhorse which could also be used \"to take the wife to church on Sunday and the pigs to the market on Monday\".\n\nIn 1956, the company bought a large tract of land in the northern [[Melbourne]] suburb of [[Campbellfield, Victoria|Campbellfield]], and in July 1961 announced that the new Melbourne factory would become the company headquarters.<ref name=gex150 />\n\nFord Australia is one of Ford's five product development centres globally, and will continue to design and develop cars and trucks for the Asia/Pacific region after the closure of the manufacturing arm. It was expected to retain about 1300 workers in Australia.<ref>http://www.motoring.com.au/ford-splits-australian-hq-49272/</ref>\n\n=== End of Australian production ===\nIn 2009, the parent Ford company, seeking to avoid the Chapter 11 bankruptcy that had already befallen General Motors and Chrysler, began abandoning overseas projects. Around July 2009 Ford Australia had received permission from Detroit to add a new small car to its Falcon production line. On 23 May 2013, Ford Australia announced that it would stop making cars after 88 years due to uncompetitive manufacturing costs and lacklustre sales. The carmaker's annual financial report, for the previous year, showed a loss of A$141m dollars (\u00a390m/$136m) after tax for the 2012 financial year. This followed a loss of A$290m in 2011 and a total loss of A$600m over the preceding five years, as a result, 1,200 staff would lose their jobs.<ref>{{cite news|last=.co.uk|first=Guardian|title=Ford Australia to stop making cars|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/may/23/ford-australia-stop-making-cars|location=London|work=The Guardian|date=23 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nFord had two main factories, both in [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]]: located in the [[Geelong]] suburb of [[Norlane, Victoria|Norlane]] and the northern Melbourne suburb of Campbellfield. The [[Ford Discovery Centre]], a museum of the history of the Ford Motor Company in Australia that was also located in Geelong, closed; the site is now been occupied by [[Deakin University]].\n\nFrom 1972 to 2016, Ford Falcons were fully Australian designed. It also produced the [[Ford Territory (Australia)|Territory]], which also ended production in 2016. Production of the Falcon ended with the closure of the Broadmeadows (Campbellfield) and Geelong engine and panel stamping plants. The Geelong factory produced its last Australian-made straight-six and V8 engines on 26 September 2016. Assembly at Broadmeadows ended on 7 October 2016.\n\n== Sites ==\n[[File:Ford stamping plant Geelong.jpg|thumb|Stamping plant at Geelong (closed 2016)]]\n\nFord has also designated as one of five (worldwide) full-service Regional Product Development Centre, specifically for the Asia Pacific and African regions. Products launched so far include the Ford Ikon and [[Ford Fiesta|Fiesta]] in India and the [[Ford Bantam]] ute and [[Ford Ikon|Ikon]] (a sedan version of the Fiesta) in South Africa, and has also developed the new Ranger.<ref>[http://media.ford.com/newsroom/release_display.cfm?release=23353 Ford Motor Company \u2013 Press Release \u2013 FORD AUSTRALIA ANNOUNCES MAJOR NEW PROJECTS<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612184143/http://media.ford.com/newsroom/release_display.cfm?release=23353 |date=12 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2019, engineers and designers were among more than 100 workers to lose their jobs at Ford in Victoria. About 40 salaried workers, 75 hourly workers and 90 contractors across Ford bases in Broadmeadows, Lara and Geelong will be affected, the company confirmed, as the automaker further consolidates its operations. Ford's engineering work on its Ranger ute and other models \"will be led out of the United States\", the company said in a statement. Remaining Australian-based engineers will have a \"strategic role\" in developing a new medium-sized pick-up truck for Ford and the German brand, the automaker said.<ref>https://www.sbs.com.au/news/more-than-100-ford-jobs-cut-in-victoria.</ref>\n\n== Models produced ==\nFord Australia started by assembling Model Ts. As Ford introduced new models, these were assembled in Australia. During World War II, Ford Australia ceased producing cars to commence military production to support the war effort.\n\nAfter World War II, Ford recommenced assembly of imported Ford models. Initially, they assembled the UK sourced [[Ford Pilot|Pilot]], then a range of British cars, including the [[Ford Prefect|Prefect]], [[Ford Anglia|Anglia]], [[Ford Consul|Consul]], [[Ford Zephyr|Zephyr]] and [[Ford Zodiac|Zodiac]]. Ford also assembled the Canadian Ford V8.\n\n=== Hatchback ===\nThe [[Ford Laser]] was produced in Ford's plant at [[Homebush, New South Wales|Homebush]] in Sydney, from 1981 until September 1994 when the plant closed, after which they were fully imported from Japan. The Laser was replaced by the [[Ford Focus]] in 2002. It is currently offered in sedan and hatchback variants with a 2.0L engine, which is one of the market leaders in sales. The [[Ford Fiesta|Fiesta]], a global Ford product, has also been offered since 2004.\n\n=== Mid-size ===\nMid-size cars assembled in Australia included the [[Ford Cortina]], [[Ford Capri|Capri]] and [[Ford Escort (Europe)|Escort]], from the UK. These were adapted for the Australian market: for example, from 1972, the Cortina was available with the option of either a 3.3-litre or 4.1-litre six-cylinder engine, and the Escort could be offered across the range with the Cortina's 2.0-litre motor. In 1977, lack of capacity meant that the Cortina wagon was in fact assembled in [[Renault]]'s (now long since closed) Australian factory in [[Heidelberg, Victoria]].\n\nThe Cortina's replacement, the [[Mazda 626]]-based [[Ford Telstar|Telstar]], was initially assembled in Australia. In 1989 the Telstar sedan was replaced by the locally assembled [[Ford Corsair]] which was basically a rebadged [[Nissan Pintara]]. When Nissan shut down its Australian manufacturing operations in 1992 the Telstar nameplate was reintroduced, and as before it was a rebadged and respecced Mazda 626. In 1995 the Telstar was dropped in favour of the [[Ford Mondeo|Mondeo]], imported from [[Belgium]].\n\nFord Australia dropped the Mondeo in 2001, arguing at the time that the segment of the market in which it competed was in decline, but in 2007, it announced that it would introduce the new [[Ford Mondeo#Mk IV (2007)|Mk IV]] model in Australia.<ref>[http://www.drive.com.au/Editorial/MiniSite/MiniSiteArticleDetail.aspx?ArticleID=36535&vf=28&MiniSiteID=4 Ford confirms Mondeo's return to Oz] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111120434/http://www.drive.com.au/Editorial/MiniSite/MiniSiteArticleDetail.aspx?ArticleID=36535&vf=28&MiniSiteID=4 |date=11 November 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Large car ===\n[[File:2015 Ford Falcon (FG X) G6E Turbo (2017-11-18) 01.jpg|thumb|[[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Ford Falcon]] (1960\u20132016)]]\n\nThe Ford Falcon was manufactured in Australia according to its North American design, with the first model rolling off the production line at Ford's Broadmeadows plant on 28 June 1960. It differed little from the American design apart from conversion to [[right hand drive]], and the Falcon soon proved unable to cope on harsh Australian roads, sparking a massive effort to introduce running engineering changes to improve its reliability. By the mid-1960s, the car was substantially different from its North American cousin and was offered in sedan, wagon, coupe, utility and panel van styles.\n\nProduction of the North American Falcon, upon which the Falcon was now loosely based, ended in 1970, forcing Australia to go it alone on design. The first true all-Australian Ford Falcon arrived with the XA model in June 1972.\n\nThe Falcon had been an Australian automotive icon for most of its 56 years in production, playing a prominent part in Australian life, popular culture and motor racing. Falcons have served as taxis, police cars, family runabouts, transport for tradespeople and have been the winning car many times in the Australian Touring Car Championship and at the annual Bathurst 1000 touring car race, where the Falcon's reputation for engineering excellence was cemented by the early 1970s through the Falcon GT and GTHO muscle car variants.\n\nFord has manufactured more than four million units since 1960, and has topped the sales charts on many occasions. Until 2016, the Falcon line-up was offered in sedan and utility body styles, however in the past panel vans, station wagons, and hardtops were offered. Falcons had dominated the ranks of taxis in Australia and New Zealand, along with sister car, the Ford Fairlane. Performance variants of the Falcon have been used extensively for pursuit work for many years.\n\n=== Luxury car ===\nFord Australia produced a range of full-size luxury cars alongside the Falcon for most of its production history. These models were named the [[Ford Fairlane (Australia)|Fairlane]] and the LTD. The first Fairlane was released in 1959 and was an Australian assembled version of the [[1957 Ford|Fairlane]] from the USA. This process of assembling American cars would continue until 1967 where Ford Australia would design its own luxury car, the ZA Fairlane. The ZA Fairlane was heavily based on the existing XR Falcon with an extended wheelbase, longer boot and styling changes. The car was released to critical acclaim and quickly established the Australian luxury car market as its own.\n\nFord Fairlanes were preferred vehicles among politicians and businessmen and was seen as the pinnacle of Australian automotive engineering and prestige. The second generation of Fairlane, introduced in 1972 brought a new model into the Australian luxury car market, the LTD. The LTD in effect was a Fairlane with even more luxury features such as retractable headlights, a vinyl roof and an even longer wheelbase. From the third generation of Fairlane onwards, the LTD shared the same wheelbase and body as the Fairlane with it being pitched as a more luxurious version of the Fairlane rather than being a completely different car.\n\nThe Fairlane sat on top of the Australian luxury car sales charts for many decades before its gradual downfall starting in the late 1980s with the rising import of foreign luxury cars such as BMW and Mercedes Benz. By the turn of the millennium, the Fairlane had been overtaken by the [[Holden Caprice|Holden Statesman]] in sales. In 2007, Ford Australia announced it would be cancelling further production of the Fairlane and LTD beyond the 2007 model year, citing falling sales and an uncertain future in the full-size luxury market. With the backing of large volume foreign exports, this left the Holden Statesman and Caprice as the sole players in the full-size extended wheelbase Australian luxury car market until their demise in 2017.\n\n=== SUV ===\n[[File:2015 Ford Territory (SZ II) TX AWD wagon (2015-07-03) 01.jpg|thumb|Ford Territory (2004\u20132016)]]\n\nBetween 2004 and 2016, the [[Ford Territory (Australia)|Ford Territory]] had been built on the same production line as the Falcon. The Territory (technically a [[crossover SUV|crossover]]) had regularly been the most popular SUV in Australia since its release.<ref>[http://www.overlander.com.au/vehicle_tests/index/full/232/4WD-Of-The-Year-2005 4WD Of The Year 2004 \u2013 Vehicle Tests \u2013 Overlander 4WD Magazine \u2013 Australia's leading four wheel drive magazine<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080611132249/http://www.overlander.com.au/vehicle_tests/index/full/232/4WD-Of-The-Year-2005 |date=11 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\n=== Current vehicle range ===\n(As of March 2020)\n\n==== Cars ====\n* [[Ford Focus]]\n* [[Ford Fiesta]] (ST 5-door only)\n\n==== Performance ====\n* [[Ford Fiesta ST]]\n* [[Ford Focus ST]]\n* [[Ford Mustang]]\n* [[Ford Raptor]]\n\n==== Family SUVs ====\n* [[Ford Puma (crossover)|Ford Puma]]\n* [[Ford Escape]]\n\n==== Large SUVs ====\n* [[Ford Everest]]\n* [[Ford Edge#Second generation (2015\u2013present)|Ford Endura]]\n\n==== Commercial vehicles ====\n* [[Ford Transit]]\n* [[Ford Transit Custom]]\n* [[Ford Ranger (T6)|Ford Ranger]]\n\n=== Former vehicle range in production ===\n\n==== Small Cars ====\n* [[Ford Fiesta]]\n\n==== Family Cars ====\n* [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Ford Falcon]] (1960-2016)\n*[[Ford Escort (Europe)|Ford Escort]] (1970-1981)\n*[[Ford Cortina]] (1964-1982)\n*[[Ford Capri]] (1969-1972)\n* [[Ford Corsair]] (1989-1992)\n*[[Ford_Capri_(Australia)|Ford Capri]] / [[Mercury_Capri#Third_Generation_(1991\u20131994)|Mercury Capri Convertible (1989-1994)]]\n*[[Ford Meteor]] (1981-1987)\n*[[Ford Laser]] (1981-1994)\n*[[Ford Telstar]] (1982-1994) \n*[[Ford Mondeo]] (2007-2020)\n\n==== Luxury Cars ====\n* [[Ford Fairlane (Australia)|Ford Fairlane]] (1967-2007)\n* [[Ford Fairlane (Australia)|Ford LTD]] (1973-2007)\n* [[Ford Mondeo]] (Titanium) (2007-2019)\n==== Performance Cars ====\n*  Ford Falcon XR6 Turbo (2002-2016)\n*  Ford Falcon XR8 (1992-2016)\n*  Falcon GT (1967-1976, 1992; 1997; 2003-2014)\n*  Falcon GT-HO (1969-1972)\n\n==== Family SUVs ====\n* [[Ford Territory (Australia)|Ford Territory]] (2004-2016)\n* [[Ford Ecosport]] (2013-2020)\n\n==== Commercial vehicles ====\n\n* [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Ford Falcon Ute]] (1961\u20132016)\n* [[Ford Courier]] (1973-2007)\n* [[Ford Transit]] (1966-1982)\n\n{{see also|Ford Performance Vehicles|Tickford Vehicle Engineering}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\nhttps://www.sbs.com.au/news/more-than-100-ford-jobs-cut-in-victoria\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ford.com.au Ford Australia]\n\n{{Ford Australia timeline}}\n{{Ford Motor Company}}\n{{Automotive industry in Australia}}\n\n[[Category:Ford Australia| ]]\n[[Category:Ford Motor Company|*]]\n[[Category:Australian subsidiaries of foreign companies]]\n[[Category:Car manufacturers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Heritage-listed buildings in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing plants in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicle manufacturers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 1925]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Ford Motor Company of Australia Limited\n| logo = Ford_logo_flat.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| type = Subsidiary of [[Ford Motor Company]] of the United States\n| industry = [[Automotive]]\n| foundation = 1925\n| founder = [[Henry Ford]]\n| location = [[Richmond, Victoria|Richmond, Melbourne]] (Head Office)<br>[[Campbellfield, Victoria|Campbellfield, Melbourne]] (Asia Pacific Engineering Centre)\n| key_people = Kay Hart, CEO\n| num_employees = 1300<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ford.com.au/aboutfordaustralia |title=About Ford \u2013 Australia |publisher=Ford Australia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052609/http://www.ford.com.au/aboutfordaustralia |archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.ford.com.au}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Ford norlane.jpg|right|thumb|Ford factory in [[Norlane, Victoria]], 1957.]]\n\nThe '''Ford Motor Company of Australia Limited''', known by its trading name '''Ford Australia''', is the Australian subsidiary of [[Automotive industry in the United States|United States-based automaker]] [[Ford Motor Company]]. It was founded in [[Geelong]], Victoria, in 1925 as an outpost of [[Ford Motor Company of Canada, Limited]]. At that time, Ford Canada was a separate company from Ford USA. [[Henry Ford]] had granted the manufacturing rights of Ford motor vehicles in the British Empire (later the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]]), except the United Kingdom, to Canadian investors.\n\nFord Australia's first products were Model Ts assembled from [[Complete knock down|complete knock-down (CKD) kits]] provided by Ford of Canada. It is best known in more recent times for having produced the [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Falcon]], originally a US model introduced in Australia in 1960, but adapted to Australian requirements and road conditions.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:TModel launch Geelong.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ford Model T]] parked outside the [[Geelong]] Library at its launch in Australia in 1925]]\n[[File:Ford geelong construction.jpg|thumb|right|The Ford Australia plant under construction in [[Geelong]], 1926.]]\n\nOn 31 March 1925, Ford announced that [[Geelong]], was to be the Australian headquarters. The first Australian-built Ford was a [[Ford Model T|Model T]] that came off an improvised production line in a disused Geelong wool storage warehouse in June 1925, while work started on a factory in the nearby suburb of Norlane. In 1928 the factory switched to the [[Ford Model A (1927)|Model A]] and was followed by the [[1932 Ford|Ford V8]] in 1932.<ref name=gex150>{{cite book | author = Peter Begg | title = Geelong \u2013 The First 150 Years | publisher = Globe Press | year = 1990 | isbn = 0-9592863-5-7 | page = }}</ref>\n\nIn 1934, the company released a [[coupe utility]] based upon the Model A American Ford \"Closed Cab Pickup Truck\" that had been produced for 6 years from 1928. The local designer was Ford engineer [[Lewis Bandt|Louis (Lewis) Bandt]].<ref name=gex150 /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/bandt-louis-thornett-lewis-12169/text21807|title=Bandt, Louis Thornett (Lewis) (1910\u20131987)  |author=Damian Veltri |publisher= [[Australian Dictionary of Biography]], National Centre of Biography, [[Australian National University]] |accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> During the [[Great Depression]], banks would not extend credit to farmers to purchase passenger cars- in the belief they were unnecessary luxuries. However, they would lend money for the purchase of \"working\" vehicles. The coupe utility fulfilled the need of farmers to have a workhorse which could also be used \"to take the wife to church on Sunday and the pigs to the market on Monday\".\n\nIn 1956, the company bought a large tract of land in the northern [[Melbourne]] suburb of [[Campbellfield, Victoria|Campbellfield]], and in July 1961 announced that the new Melbourne factory would become the company headquarters.<ref name=gex150 />\n\nFord Australia is one of Ford's five product development centres globally, and will continue to design and develop cars and trucks for the Asia/Pacific region after the closure of the manufacturing arm. It was expected to retain about 1300 workers in Australia.<ref>http://www.motoring.com.au/ford-splits-australian-hq-49272/</ref>\n\n=== End of Australian production ===\nIn 2009, the parent Ford company, seeking to avoid the Chapter 11 bankruptcy that had already befallen General Motors and Chrysler, began abandoning overseas projects. Around July 2009 Ford Australia had received permission from Detroit to add a new small car to its Falcon production line. On 23 May 2013, Ford Australia announced that it would stop making cars after 88 years due to uncompetitive manufacturing costs and lacklustre sales. The carmaker's annual financial report, for the previous year, showed a loss of A$141m dollars (\u00a390m/$136m) after tax for the 2012 financial year. This followed a loss of A$290m in 2011 and a total loss of A$600m over the preceding five years, as a result, 1,200 staff would lose their jobs.<ref>{{cite news|last=.co.uk|first=Guardian|title=Ford Australia to stop making cars|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/may/23/ford-australia-stop-making-cars|location=London|work=The Guardian|date=23 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nFord had two main factories, both in [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]]: located in the [[Geelong]] suburb of [[Norlane, Victoria|Norlane]] and the northern Melbourne suburb of Campbellfield. The [[Ford Discovery Centre]], a museum of the history of the Ford Motor Company in Australia that was also located in Geelong, closed; the site is now been occupied by [[Deakin University]].\n\nFrom 1972 to 2016, Ford Falcons were fully Australian designed. It also produced the [[Ford Territory (Australia)|Territory]], which also ended production in 2016. Production of the Falcon ended with the closure of the Broadmeadows (Campbellfield) and Geelong engine and panel stamping plants. The Geelong factory produced its last Australian-made straight-six and V8 engines on 26 September 2016. Assembly at Broadmeadows ended on 7 October 2016.\n\n== Sites ==\n[[File:Ford stamping plant Geelong.jpg|thumb|Stamping plant at Geelong (closed 2016)]]\n\nFord has also designated as one of five (worldwide) full-service Regional Product Development Centre, specifically for the Asia Pacific and African regions. Products launched so far include the Ford Ikon and [[Ford Fiesta|Fiesta]] in India and the [[Ford Bantam]] ute and [[Ford Ikon|Ikon]] (a sedan version of the Fiesta) in South Africa, and has also developed the new Ranger.<ref>[http://media.ford.com/newsroom/release_display.cfm?release=23353 Ford Motor Company \u2013 Press Release \u2013 FORD AUSTRALIA ANNOUNCES MAJOR NEW PROJECTS<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612184143/http://media.ford.com/newsroom/release_display.cfm?release=23353 |date=12 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2019, engineers and designers were among more than 100 workers to lose their jobs at Ford in Victoria. About 40 salaried workers, 75 hourly workers and 90 contractors across Ford bases in Broadmeadows, Lara and Geelong will be affected, the company confirmed, as the automaker further consolidates its operations. Ford's engineering work on its Ranger ute and other models \"will be led out of the United States\", the company said in a statement. Remaining Australian-based engineers will have a \"strategic role\" in developing a new medium-sized pick-up truck for Ford and the German brand, the automaker said.<ref>https://www.sbs.com.au/news/more-than-100-ford-jobs-cut-in-victoria.</ref>\n\n== Models produced ==\nFord Australia started by assembling Model Ts. As Ford introduced new models, these were assembled in Australia. During World War II, Ford Australia ceased producing cars to commence military production to support the war effort.\n\nAfter World War II, Ford recommenced assembly of imported Ford models. Initially, they assembled the UK sourced [[Ford Pilot|Pilot]], then a range of British cars, including the [[Ford Prefect|Prefect]], [[Ford Anglia|Anglia]], [[Ford Consul|Consul]], [[Ford Zephyr|Zephyr]] and [[Ford Zodiac|Zodiac]]. Ford also assembled the Canadian Ford V8.\n\n=== Hatchback ===\nThe [[Ford Laser]] was produced in Ford's plant at [[Homebush, New South Wales|Homebush]] in Sydney, from 1981 until September 1994 when the plant closed, after which they were fully imported from Japan. The Laser was replaced by the [[Ford Focus]] in 2002. It is currently offered in sedan and hatchback variants with a 2.0L engine, which is one of the market leaders in sales. The [[Ford Fiesta|Fiesta]], a global Ford product, has also been offered since 2004.\n\n=== Mid-size ===\nMid-size cars assembled in Australia included the [[Ford Cortina]], [[Ford Capri|Capri]] and [[Ford Escort (Europe)|Escort]], from the UK. These were adapted for the Australian market: for example, from 1972, the Cortina was available with the option of either a 3.3-litre or 4.1-litre six-cylinder engine, and the Escort could be offered across the range with the Cortina's 2.0-litre motor. In 1977, lack of capacity meant that the Cortina wagon was in fact assembled in [[Renault]]'s (now long since closed) Australian factory in [[Heidelberg, Victoria]].\n\nThe Cortina's replacement, the [[Mazda 626]]-based [[Ford Telstar|Telstar]], was initially assembled in Australia. In 1989 the Telstar sedan was replaced by the locally assembled [[Ford Corsair]] which was basically a rebadged [[Nissan Pintara]]. When Nissan shut down its Australian manufacturing operations in 1992 the Telstar nameplate was reintroduced, and as before it was a rebadged and respecced Mazda 626. In 1995 the Telstar was dropped in favour of the [[Ford Mondeo|Mondeo]], imported from [[Belgium]].\n\nFord Australia dropped the Mondeo in 2001, arguing at the time that the segment of the market in which it competed was in decline, but in 2007, it announced that it would introduce the new [[Ford Mondeo#Mk IV (2007)|Mk IV]] model in Australia.<ref>[http://www.drive.com.au/Editorial/MiniSite/MiniSiteArticleDetail.aspx?ArticleID=36535&vf=28&MiniSiteID=4 Ford confirms Mondeo's return to Oz] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111120434/http://www.drive.com.au/Editorial/MiniSite/MiniSiteArticleDetail.aspx?ArticleID=36535&vf=28&MiniSiteID=4 |date=11 November 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Large car ===\n[[File:2015 Ford Falcon (FG X) G6E Turbo (2017-11-18) 01.jpg|thumb|[[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Ford Falcon]] (1960\u20132016)]]\n\nThe Ford Falcon was manufactured in Australia according to its North American design, with the first model rolling off the production line at Ford's Broadmeadows plant on 28 June 1960. It differed little from the American design apart from conversion to [[right hand drive]], and the Falcon soon proved unable to cope on harsh Australian roads, sparking a massive effort to introduce running engineering changes to improve its reliability. By the mid-1960s, the car was substantially different from its North American cousin and was offered in sedan, wagon, coupe, utility and panel van styles.\n\nProduction of the North American Falcon, upon which the Falcon was now loosely based, ended in 1970, forcing Australia to go it alone on design. The first true all-Australian Ford Falcon arrived with the XA model in June 1972.\n\nThe Falcon had been an Australian automotive icon for most of its 56 years in production, playing a prominent part in Australian life, popular culture and motor racing. Falcons have served as taxis, police cars, family runabouts, transport for tradespeople and have been the winning car many times in the Australian Touring Car Championship and at the annual Bathurst 1000 touring car race, where the Falcon's reputation for engineering excellence was cemented by the early 1970s through the Falcon GT and GTHO muscle car variants.\n\nFord has manufactured more than four million units since 1960, and has topped the sales charts on many occasions. Until 2016, the Falcon line-up was offered in sedan and utility body styles, however in the past panel vans, station wagons, and hardtops were offered. Falcons had dominated the ranks of taxis in Australia and New Zealand, along with sister car, the Ford Fairlane. Performance variants of the Falcon have been used extensively for pursuit work for many years.\n\n=== Luxury car ===\nFord Australia produced a range of full-size luxury cars alongside the Falcon for most of its production history. These models were named the [[Ford Fairlane (Australia)|Fairlane]] and the LTD. The first Fairlane was released in 1959 and was an Australian assembled version of the [[1957 Ford|Fairlane]] from the USA. This process of assembling American cars would continue until 1967 where Ford Australia would design its own luxury car, the ZA Fairlane. The ZA Fairlane was heavily based on the existing XR Falcon with an extended wheelbase, longer boot and styling changes. The car was released to critical acclaim and quickly established the Australian luxury car market as its own.\n\nFord Fairlanes were preferred vehicles among politicians and businessmen and was seen as the pinnacle of Australian automotive engineering and prestige. The second generation of Fairlane, introduced in 1972 brought a new model into the Australian luxury car market, the LTD. The LTD in effect was a Fairlane with even more luxury features such as retractable headlights, a vinyl roof and an even longer wheelbase. From the third generation of Fairlane onwards, the LTD shared the same wheelbase and body as the Fairlane with it being pitched as a more luxurious version of the Fairlane rather than being a completely different car.\n\nThe Fairlane sat on top of the Australian luxury car sales charts for many decades before its gradual downfall starting in the late 1980s with the rising import of foreign luxury cars such as BMW and Mercedes Benz. By the turn of the millennium, the Fairlane had been overtaken by the [[Holden Caprice|Holden Statesman]] in sales. In 2007, Ford Australia announced it would be cancelling further production of the Fairlane and LTD beyond the 2007 model year, citing falling sales and an uncertain future in the full-size luxury market. With the backing of large volume foreign exports, this left the Holden Statesman and Caprice as the sole players in the full-size extended wheelbase Australian luxury car market until their demise in 2017.\n\n=== SUV ===\n[[File:2015 Ford Territory (SZ II) TX AWD wagon (2015-07-03) 01.jpg|thumb|Ford Territory (2004\u20132016)]]\n\nBetween 2004 and 2016, the [[Ford Territory (Australia)|Ford Territory]] had been built on the same production line as the Falcon. The Territory (technically a [[crossover SUV|crossover]]) had regularly been the most popular SUV in Australia since its release.<ref>[http://www.overlander.com.au/vehicle_tests/index/full/232/4WD-Of-The-Year-2005 4WD Of The Year 2004 \u2013 Vehicle Tests \u2013 Overlander 4WD Magazine \u2013 Australia's leading four wheel drive magazine<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080611132249/http://www.overlander.com.au/vehicle_tests/index/full/232/4WD-Of-The-Year-2005 |date=11 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\n=== Current vehicle range ===\n(As of March 2020)\n\n==== Cars ====\n* [[Ford Focus]]\n* [[Ford Fiesta]] (ST 5-door only)\n\n==== Performance ====\n* [[Ford Fiesta ST]]\n* [[Ford Focus ST]]\n* [[Ford Mustang]]\n* [[Ford Raptor]]\n\n==== Family SUVs ====\n* [[Ford Puma (crossover)|Ford Puma]]\n* [[Ford Escape]]\n\n==== Large SUVs ====\n* [[Ford Everest]]\n* [[Ford Edge#Second generation (2015\u2013present)|Ford Endura]]\n\n==== Commercial vehicles ====\n* [[Ford Transit]]\n* [[Ford Transit Custom]]\n* [[Ford Ranger (T6)|Ford Ranger]]\n\n=== Former vehicle range in production ===\n\n==== Small Cars ====\n* [[Ford Fiesta]]\n\n==== Family Cars ====\n* [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Ford Falcon]] (1960-2016)\n*[[Ford Escort (Europe)|Ford Escort]] (1970-1981)\n*[[Ford Cortina]] (1964-1982)\n*[[Ford Capri]] (1969-1972)\n* [[Ford Corsair]] (1989-1992)\n*[[Ford_Capri_(Australia)|Ford Capri]] / [[Mercury_Capri#Third_Generation_(1991\u20131994)|Mercury Capri Convertible (1989-1994)]]\n*[[Ford Meteor]] (1981-1987)\n*[[Ford Laser]] (1981-1994)\n*[[Ford Telstar]] (1982-1994) \n*[[Ford Mondeo]] (2007-2020)\n\n==== Luxury Cars ====\n* [[Ford Fairlane (Australia)|Ford Fairlane]] (1967-2007)\n* [[Ford Fairlane (Australia)|Ford LTD]] (1973-2007)\n* [[Ford Mondeo]] (Titanium) (2007-2019)\n==== Performance Cars ====\n*  Ford Falcon XR6 Turbo (2002-2016)\n*  Ford Falcon XR8 (1992-2016)\n*  Falcon GT (1967-1976, 1992; 1997; 2003-2014)\n*  Falcon GT-HO (1969-1972)\n\n==== Family SUVs ====\n* [[Ford Territory (Australia)|Ford Territory]] (2004-2016)\n* [[Ford Ecosport]] (2013-2020)\n\n==== Commercial vehicles ====\n\n* [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Ford Falcon Ute]] (1961\u20132016)\n* [[Ford Courier]] (1973-2007)\n* [[Ford Transit]] (1966-1982)\n\n{{see also|Ford Performance Vehicles|Tickford Vehicle Engineering}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\nhttps://www.sbs.com.au/news/more-than-100-ford-jobs-cut-in-victoria\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ford.com.au Ford Australia]\n\n{{Ford Australia timeline}}\n{{Ford Motor Company}}\n{{Automotive industry in Australia}}\n\n[[Category:Ford Australia| ]]\n[[Category:Ford Motor Company|*]]\n[[Category:Australian subsidiaries of foreign companies]]\n[[Category:Car manufacturers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Heritage-listed buildings in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing plants in Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicle manufacturers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies establi