Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Chester''' is a small rural city in [[Chester County, South Carolina]], United States. The population was 5,607 at the 2010 census,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4514095| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001): Chester city, South Carolina| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=July 1, 2015| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213064310/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4514095| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> down from 6,476 at the 2000 census. It is the [[county seat]] of [[Chester County, South Carolina|Chester County]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=2011-06-07 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150509170006/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2015-05-09 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWhile being transported to [[Richmond, Virginia]], for his trial for treason, former Vice-President [[Aaron Burr]] passed through Chester. Burr \"flung himself from his horse and cried for a rescue, but the officer commanding the escort seized him, threw him back like a child into the saddle, and marched on.\"<ref name =\"Adams\">[[Henry Adams]], ''History of the United States of America during the Administrations of Thomas Jefferson'', Library of America, 1986, p. 828.''</ref> The large stone he stood on has been inscribed and is preserved in the town center, and is known locally as the Aaron Burr Rock.\n\nChester was home to [[Brainerd Institute]], a school for African American children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scencyclopedia.org/sce/entries/brainerd-institute/|title=Brainerd Institute}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Catholic Presbyterian Church]], [[Chester City Hall and Opera House]], [[Chester Historic District]], [[Colvin-Fant-Durham Farm Complex]], [[Fishdam Ford]], [[Kumler Hall]], [[Lewis Inn]], and [[McCollum Mound]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n\n==Geography and climate==\nChester is located just west of the center of Chester County at {{coord|34|42|20|N|81|12|42|W|type:city}} (34.705553, -81.211638).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> [[U.S. Route 321]] bypasses the city to the west and the south, leading north {{Convert|22|mi}} to [[York, South Carolina|York]] and south {{convert|25|mi}} to [[Winnsboro, South Carolina|Winnsboro]]. [[South Carolina Highway 9]] passes through the city center and leads east {{convert|11|mi}} to [[Interstate 77]] near [[Richburg, South Carolina|Richburg]] and west {{convert|49|mi}} to [[Spartanburg, South Carolina|Spartanburg]]. Highways [[South Carolina Highway 72|72]] and [[South Carolina Highway 121|121]] lead northeast {{convert|19|mi}} to [[Rock Hill, South Carolina|Rock Hill]] and southwest {{convert|28|mi}} to [[Whitmire, South Carolina|Whitmire]].\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|8.5|km2|order=flip}}, all of it land.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n[[File:Springstein Mill. John Lewis (boy with hat), 12 years old, 1 year in mill. Weaver - 4 looms. 40 (cents) a day to... - NARA - 523117.jpg|right|thumb|Young mill workers in Chester, 1908, photographed by [[Lewis Hine]]]]\n\n{{Weather box \n|location = Chester, South Carolina, normals 1981\u20132010, extremes 1923-present\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 82\n|Feb record high F = 83\n|Mar record high F = 88\n|Apr record high F = 96\n|May record high F = 102\n|Jun record high F = 105\n|Jul record high F = 106\n|Aug record h